WEBVTT

00:13.250 --> 00:17.292
♪ (THEME MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

00:28.042 --> 00:31.584
Kenny G is the best-selling
instrumentalist of all time.

00:31.667 --> 00:35.542
<i>He's probably the most famous
living jazz musician.</i>

00:35.626 --> 00:38.042
<i>And I made this film to find out</i>

00:38.125 --> 00:42.459
why that makes certain people
really angry.

00:42.542 --> 00:45.792
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

00:56.709 --> 01:03.709
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

01:11.334 --> 01:12.751
PENNY LANE: How are you feeling?

01:13.584 --> 01:14.626
Um...

01:15.417 --> 01:16.959
Underappreciated in general.

01:17.042 --> 01:19.792
-(PENNY LAUGHING)
-But other than that I'm fine.

01:19.876 --> 01:21.584
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

01:21.667 --> 01:24.209
KENNY G:<i> I never get</i>
<i>to go anywhere</i>
<i>without playing the sax.</i>

01:24.292 --> 01:27.417
<i>Honestly if I get invited
to a party,</i>

01:27.500 --> 01:28.792
it's only because
they want me to play.

01:28.876 --> 01:30.334
So I'm never really
invited anywhere

01:30.417 --> 01:31.792
-just because of me.
-PENNY: I disbelieve that...

01:31.876 --> 01:33.250
It's like, "You're gonna
play, aren't you?"

01:33.334 --> 01:35.751
-...I don't believe that at all.
-Oh. It's 100 percent true.

01:35.834 --> 01:38.751
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:38.834 --> 01:40.000
KENNY G:<i> I think people</i>

01:40.083 --> 01:42.042
<i>don't know me very well,
because it's a...</i>

01:42.125 --> 01:44.167
You know, they know my music.
They don't really know me.

01:44.250 --> 01:46.792
I'm not a-- I don't think
I'm a personality to people.

01:46.876 --> 01:48.542
I think I'm a sound.

01:48.626 --> 01:55.292
♪ (UPBEAT SAXOPHONE
NOTES PLAYING) ♪

02:12.334 --> 02:14.209
-♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES STOP) ♪
-I almost had it. Shit.

02:15.167 --> 02:16.209
(BLOWS)

02:16.292 --> 02:18.042
I think you got enough
of this backstage right now.

02:18.125 --> 02:19.209
Don't you think? Yeah.

02:19.292 --> 02:20.834
Thanks, guys.

02:24.167 --> 02:26.000
TECH:
<i>Stand by for house lights.</i>

02:26.834 --> 02:27.876
<i>Ready?</i>

02:28.667 --> 02:35.584
(CROWD CHEERS, APPLAUDS)

02:35.667 --> 02:41.500
(APPLAUSE CONTINUES)

02:49.959 --> 02:52.042
PENNY: We're gonna start
by listening
to some Kenny songs.

02:52.125 --> 02:54.500
-(CHUCKLES)
-PENNY: Um, you can talk
as much as you want,

02:54.584 --> 02:56.918
or just listen,
it's totally up to you.

02:57.667 --> 03:00.042
♪ ("SONGBIRD" PLAYING) ♪

03:05.959 --> 03:09.500
♪ (SONG CONTINUES) ♪

03:12.417 --> 03:14.542
PENNY: Do you remember
the first time
you heard this song?

03:15.334 --> 03:16.417
No.

03:17.667 --> 03:19.167
Absolutely not.

03:19.250 --> 03:22.167
♪ (SONG CONTINUES) ♪

03:25.709 --> 03:28.334
When you first called me
and said,

03:28.417 --> 03:30.083
"I'm doing a Kenny G
documentary,"

03:30.167 --> 03:32.292
I had to think about
my own relationship

03:32.375 --> 03:34.125
to Kenny G and to his music,

03:34.209 --> 03:36.000
um, 'cause I don't know
anyone out there

03:36.083 --> 03:38.459
who's like a Kenny G scholar
per se.

03:38.542 --> 03:41.000
Um, so I had to really think
about, like,

03:41.083 --> 03:43.709
what is my intellectual...
(CHUCKLES)

03:43.792 --> 03:46.125
...artistic relationship
to Kenny G's music?

03:46.209 --> 03:48.083
He's just sort of part
of the musical furniture

03:48.167 --> 03:50.876
of American culture
since the late '80s.

03:50.959 --> 03:52.459
♪ ("SILHOUETTE" PLAYING) ♪

03:52.542 --> 03:54.542
BEN RATLIFF:<i> I'm sure I heard</i>
<i>a lot of Kenny G</i>

03:54.626 --> 03:57.250
<i>while waiting for something.</i>

03:57.334 --> 04:02.375
At a dentist's office,
for example, or in a bank.

04:02.459 --> 04:05.250
And so, I think
I associated his music

04:05.334 --> 04:10.083
with a corporate attempt
to soothe my nerves.

04:10.167 --> 04:13.167
And I didn't like that.
You know, I don't like that.

04:13.250 --> 04:14.334
(CHUCKLES)

04:14.417 --> 04:18.042
No, I'm being treated
like an ant or something.

04:19.083 --> 04:22.083
♪ ("FOREVER IN LOVE" PLAYING) ♪

04:26.167 --> 04:29.167
It feels like
he's pouring a sidewalk,

04:29.250 --> 04:32.125
and the music is just, like,
layered in there,

04:32.209 --> 04:36.500
and it's just this thin,
and it's shiny.

04:36.584 --> 04:40.083
He makes "nice" music
for nice people,

04:40.167 --> 04:41.959
and I don't suppose I should
begrudge anybody

04:42.042 --> 04:44.542
coming home from their job
and relaxing to that.

04:44.626 --> 04:48.209
What it makes me feel
is that it's just wallpaper.

04:48.292 --> 04:51.292
I don't know, I just want to
believe I'm better than that.

04:51.375 --> 04:56.709
I get a little knotted up
and confused when--

04:56.792 --> 04:59.542
If I have to talk about Kenny G.

04:59.626 --> 05:03.375
With Kenny G's music,
what can you say?

05:04.500 --> 05:06.709
I don't know.
What can you say?

05:09.709 --> 05:11.792
Want me to sit in this chair
and you can check it out with--?

05:11.876 --> 05:13.959
-PENNY: Yeah, check it out.
-With the real vibe here?

05:14.626 --> 05:16.209
Um...

05:16.292 --> 05:18.500
Sweater on this, over this,
would you like better,

05:18.584 --> 05:19.792
or do you just like this shirt?

05:19.876 --> 05:21.959
-PENNY: I love that shirt.
-Great then.

05:22.042 --> 05:24.834
PENNY: Um,
so my first question for you is,

05:24.918 --> 05:27.542
what do you love about music?

05:28.417 --> 05:30.250
What do I love about music?

05:31.500 --> 05:33.751
I don't know if I love music
that much.

05:33.834 --> 05:34.918
I do...

05:36.417 --> 05:37.959
What do I love about music?

05:39.375 --> 05:41.375
I guess, for me,
when I listen to music,

05:41.459 --> 05:43.500
I think about the musicians.

05:43.584 --> 05:46.375
And I just think about
what it takes to make that music

05:46.459 --> 05:47.918
and how much they had
to practice,

05:48.000 --> 05:49.918
and how good they had to be.

05:50.000 --> 05:55.042
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

05:55.125 --> 05:58.167
KENNY G:<i> I practice every day,</i>
<i>three hours every day.</i>

05:58.250 --> 05:59.876
Could I practice two? Probably.

05:59.959 --> 06:01.334
Could I practice five? Probably.

06:01.417 --> 06:03.209
See? I get more excited
about that.

06:03.292 --> 06:10.375
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

06:15.209 --> 06:18.083
That's a hard lick.
I just played it really well.

06:18.167 --> 06:21.876
I don't think there's anything
wrong with hard work,

06:21.959 --> 06:24.209
practice, preparation,

06:24.292 --> 06:26.584
and... not "perfection,"

06:26.667 --> 06:29.751
but at least trying,
striving for it.

06:29.834 --> 06:31.792
Trying your best
to strive for that.

06:31.876 --> 06:33.292
I don't think anybody can say

06:33.375 --> 06:34.667
there's anything
wrong with that.

06:34.751 --> 06:36.125
That can't be wrong.

06:36.209 --> 06:38.626
I think that's why my career's
lasted this long.

06:39.667 --> 06:40.792
I'm hoping so,

06:40.876 --> 06:43.292
because that way
I'll continue to do it.

06:43.375 --> 06:45.918
Put your hands together
for Kenny G.

06:46.000 --> 06:50.209
(CROWD CHEERING)

06:51.292 --> 06:57.500
♪ (MELODIC SAXOPHONE
MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

07:02.042 --> 07:05.959
JASON KING:<i> The 1980s and 1990s</i>
<i>represented a peak moment</i>

07:06.042 --> 07:09.375
for a kind of mass monoculture.

07:10.375 --> 07:11.459
<i>There was an attempt</i>

07:11.542 --> 07:14.167
<i>to try to sell artists,
superstar artists,</i>

07:14.250 --> 07:16.292
<i>to the widest possible audience,</i>

07:16.375 --> 07:18.834
<i>and Kenny G is
one of those artists.</i>

07:18.918 --> 07:22.834
PAT PRESCOTT:<i> He was</i>
<i>this white boy</i>
<i>with the naturally curly hair,</i>

07:22.918 --> 07:25.292
you know, who looked
very ordinary.

07:25.375 --> 07:27.292
Almost a little nerdy, even.

07:27.375 --> 07:31.125
<i>But he had such a beautiful
tone on the saxophone,</i>

07:31.209 --> 07:33.709
and captured the imagination
of people.

07:33.792 --> 07:36.417
Play that funky music,
white boy.

07:37.459 --> 07:40.209
♪ (JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

07:40.292 --> 07:42.334
WILL SMITH:<i> He's one</i>
<i>of the very few jazz artists</i>

07:42.417 --> 07:45.000
<i>to move from the jazz
to the pop charts.</i>

07:45.083 --> 07:46.292
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

07:46.375 --> 07:49.751
the number-one-selling
instrumentalist of all time,

07:50.500 --> 07:51.751
Kenny G!

07:52.626 --> 07:55.042
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS)

07:55.125 --> 07:56.667
Are you sure this is right?

07:57.918 --> 07:59.042
Are you positive?

08:00.667 --> 08:02.292
CHRIS WASHBURNE:
<i>The fact of the matter is,</i>

08:02.375 --> 08:04.334
<i>Kenny G, in the 1990s,</i>

08:04.417 --> 08:07.292
was one of the most well-known
musicians on this planet.

08:09.000 --> 08:10.542
TV HOST:<i> How does it feel</i>
<i>knowing that</i>

08:10.626 --> 08:14.584
<i>you are the favorite musician
of President Bill Clinton?</i>

08:14.667 --> 08:16.167
-Well, what can I say?
-TV HOST: I know.

08:16.250 --> 08:19.042
I mean, I'm flattered
that anybody likes my music.

08:19.834 --> 08:21.125
CHRIS:<i> If you'd ask people,</i>

08:21.209 --> 08:23.083
"Name one jazz musician,"

08:23.167 --> 08:26.167
it's not gonna be Miles Davis
or John Coltrane.

08:26.250 --> 08:27.792
<i>Many times, it's Kenny G.</i>

08:27.876 --> 08:31.209
REPORTER:<i> Billboard Magazine's</i>
<i>Jazz Artist of the Decade.</i>

08:31.292 --> 08:32.250
-That's amazing.
-Amazing.

08:32.334 --> 08:33.459
What do you think about that?

08:33.542 --> 08:36.292
Because you were an
accounting major in college.

08:36.375 --> 08:38.083
TV HOST 2:<i> I would like</i>
<i>you to demonstrate</i>

08:38.167 --> 08:41.417
<i>the circle breathing technique
that you have patented.</i>

08:41.500 --> 08:43.209
Could you describe it
and then do it?

08:43.292 --> 08:45.751
Well, I don't know
if it's my patent, but...

08:45.834 --> 08:46.918
it's basically--

08:47.000 --> 08:48.375
TV HOST 2:<i> You don't breathe,</i>
<i>is basically it.</i>

08:48.459 --> 08:51.375
KENNY G:<i> You breathe</i>
<i>while you play at the same time.</i>

08:51.459 --> 08:53.375
♪ (HOLDING SINGLE NOTE) ♪

08:53.459 --> 08:56.751
And a new honor today
for sax superstar Kenny G.

08:56.834 --> 08:58.918
<i>He's made it into the Guinness
Book of World Records</i>

08:59.000 --> 09:02.709
<i>for holding the longest
sustained note ever.</i>

09:02.792 --> 09:05.584
♪ (LOW QUIET NOTE PLAYS) ♪

09:05.667 --> 09:08.292
Forty-five minutes,
forty-seven seconds.

09:08.375 --> 09:11.042
Now, that undoubtedly
is a new world record.

09:11.125 --> 09:13.626
-Congratulations.
-Thank you. Thanks.

09:13.709 --> 09:15.209
PAT:<i> Such an interesting person,</i>

09:15.292 --> 09:17.918
<i>because at the same time
that he is one of the most</i>

09:18.000 --> 09:20.209
<i>loved characters in jazz,</i>

09:20.292 --> 09:22.626
he is also one of the most
hated people.

09:22.709 --> 09:25.542
And I won't say-- I can't--
I shouldn't say "hated."

09:25.626 --> 09:29.125
Kenny G has a Christmas album
out this year.

09:29.209 --> 09:33.209
Hey, happy birthday, Jesus.
Hope you like crap.

09:33.292 --> 09:36.792
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS, APPLAUDS)

09:39.167 --> 09:41.167
I remember hearing those songs,

09:41.250 --> 09:44.417
and I also remember
that the...

09:44.500 --> 09:47.000
denigration when it came
after Kenny G

09:47.083 --> 09:49.667
that was, you know, really,
like, over the top.

09:49.751 --> 09:51.167
♪ (OUT OF TUNE MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

09:51.250 --> 09:52.959
-No!
-No!

09:53.042 --> 09:55.334
-Kenny G?
-♪ (SAXOPHONE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

09:55.417 --> 09:56.792
<i>And I don't remember exactly</i>

09:56.876 --> 09:59.792
<i>what my reaction to it
at the time was.</i>

09:59.876 --> 10:02.375
<i>I mean, I myself,
might have like,</i>

10:02.459 --> 10:05.209
joined in with...
(CHUCKLES) ...with the choir.

10:05.292 --> 10:07.125
♪ ("SONGBIRD" PLAYS) ♪

10:07.209 --> 10:10.459
JOHN HALLE:<i> Even today</i>
<i>you can go on the Internet</i>

10:10.542 --> 10:12.292
and just google "Kenny G,"

10:12.375 --> 10:14.375
<i>and find all sorts of abuse.</i>

10:14.459 --> 10:16.083
♪ (KENNY G SONG PLAYS) ♪

10:16.167 --> 10:18.918
-We going all night
with this one!
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

10:19.000 --> 10:21.083
I don't-- I don't care
for Kenny G. I'm not into it.

10:21.167 --> 10:22.709
I don't like all that...

10:23.334 --> 10:25.375
(IMITATES SAXOPHONE)

10:27.542 --> 10:30.083
-NEWS ANCHOR 1:
Oh, It's awful, that's awful.
-(NEWS ANCHOR 2 LAUGHS)

10:30.167 --> 10:32.542
NEWS ANCHOR 3:
Some people might think
this is easy listening.

10:32.626 --> 10:35.209
-It's "Songbird."
It's my-- It's ringtone.
-(NEWS ANCHORS LAUGH)

10:35.292 --> 10:36.709
NEWS ANCHOR 4:
There's nothing easy about this.

10:36.792 --> 10:38.167
Oh, I was about to pick up
my phone.

10:38.250 --> 10:40.042
I thought suddenly
it was KG calling.

10:40.125 --> 10:42.417
-Make it stop, Mel, please!
-(NEWS ANCHORS LAUGH)

10:42.500 --> 10:44.209
KENNY G:<i> When you hear</i>
<i>that word, "easy listening,"</i>

10:44.292 --> 10:46.209
it almost sounds bad like...

10:46.292 --> 10:47.334
Well, I don't see anything wrong

10:47.417 --> 10:48.876
with something
that's easy to listen to.

10:48.959 --> 10:51.542
But, that said,
I'm not writing music

10:51.626 --> 10:52.834
so it's easy to listen to.

10:52.918 --> 10:55.375
I'm writing music
that just appeals to me.

10:55.459 --> 10:58.375
These are songs from my heart.
This is the way I just hear it.

10:58.459 --> 11:02.334
The fact that what appeals to me
also appeals to other people...

11:02.417 --> 11:04.000
that's the beautiful thing.

11:04.083 --> 11:08.417
<i>Most of the music critics
are not kind to me,</i>

11:08.500 --> 11:09.667
<i>because most
of the music critics</i>

11:09.751 --> 11:12.459
<i>aren't happy
with my style of jazz.</i>

11:12.542 --> 11:15.209
<i>They think I've decided
to play these kind of songs</i>

11:15.292 --> 11:17.209
<i>because I knew
they would sell well</i>

11:17.292 --> 11:20.000
and I could get rich and famous.

11:21.542 --> 11:23.083
If only I was that smart.

11:24.834 --> 11:29.959
(PLANE ENGINE WHIRRING)

11:32.709 --> 11:34.292
KENNY G: And we are now...

11:35.417 --> 11:36.751
Now we're flying.

11:36.834 --> 11:38.584
-(PENNY CHEERS)
-How about that.

11:39.792 --> 11:41.334
That is pretty cool.

11:41.417 --> 11:44.542
I'm gonna make this flight,
you know, stellar.

11:44.626 --> 11:46.250
And I feel the same way
when I do a concert.

11:46.334 --> 11:49.250
It's like, when I get on stage,
I don't want it to be just okay.

11:49.334 --> 11:50.751
"Yeah, he did all right."

11:50.834 --> 11:53.459
No, it's gonna be
my fricking best.

11:53.542 --> 11:56.000
And it's gonna be, like,
not just my best,

11:56.083 --> 11:58.000
it's gonna be the best.

11:58.083 --> 12:01.209
And now you can see
downtown Seattle from here.

12:01.292 --> 12:02.792
Never thought I'd be flying
my own plane

12:02.876 --> 12:05.292
over my old high school,
that's for sure.

12:08.083 --> 12:10.876
KENNY G:<i> See, I just think,</i>
<i>walking in with the sax is--</i>

12:10.959 --> 12:12.417
<i>It's-- It's more iconic.</i>

12:12.500 --> 12:14.083
PENNY:
<i>Okay, fine, do it with the sax.</i>

12:23.000 --> 12:25.167
KENNY G:<i> I don't think</i>
<i>I ever came in this way.</i>

12:25.250 --> 12:27.959
The band room is on
the other side of the school.

12:28.042 --> 12:30.125
I would come in
that way every morning,

12:30.209 --> 12:31.334
'cause we started at 7:00,

12:31.417 --> 12:33.334
and school didn't open
till 8:00.

12:34.834 --> 12:35.709
Hey!

12:35.792 --> 12:38.167
-This is the principal.
-Yes, right.

12:38.250 --> 12:39.959
You know, here's what's weird.

12:40.042 --> 12:41.334
I'm older than the principal.

12:41.417 --> 12:43.000
-(KENNY G LAUGHING)
-PRINCIPAL: Yeah, well, I'd love

12:43.083 --> 12:44.667
to get you
to sign the wall here.

12:44.751 --> 12:47.500
-We've got the signature wall.
-KENNY G: Hey.
It'd be my pleasure.

12:47.584 --> 12:49.459
I've got to think
of something inspirational.

12:49.542 --> 12:51.000
PRINCIPAL: An inspirational
note, if you can.

12:51.083 --> 12:53.459
-Not to put you on the spot.
-No, no, it's just--

12:53.542 --> 12:54.959
PRINCIPAL: But we'd love to...

12:55.042 --> 12:56.792
KENNY G: I want-- Now this is
a lot of pressure

12:56.876 --> 12:58.959
to put the right words down,
okay?

12:59.042 --> 13:01.000
'Cause you know how long
it takes me to make a record.

13:01.083 --> 13:02.709
Okay, I got to think
of something. Gosh.

13:02.792 --> 13:04.626
-This is hard!
-(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

13:04.709 --> 13:05.959
Um...

13:06.042 --> 13:07.250
(CLICKS TONGUE)

13:08.834 --> 13:10.876
Hmm.

13:10.959 --> 13:13.876
Let me see, I got to picture
what it's gonna look like.

13:17.834 --> 13:20.042
KENNY G: Okay. Uh...
(CLICKS TONGUE)

13:24.417 --> 13:26.542
Okay, here we go.
You ready? Okay.

13:46.167 --> 13:48.167
Yeah, I like that.
I think that's good.

13:48.250 --> 13:49.626
-That okay?
-PRINCIPAL: That's awesome.

13:49.709 --> 13:52.000
-That's really cool.
-Whew! Oh, my God.

13:52.083 --> 13:53.834
Okay, Drew, that was a lot
of pressure.

13:53.918 --> 13:55.417
Thanks for allowing me
to do that.

13:55.500 --> 13:57.250
PRINCIPAL: Of course,
it's a beautiful
message, thank you.

13:57.334 --> 13:59.751
That's really... I'm honored.

13:59.834 --> 14:02.209
I really am, I'm really honored
to be on that wall.

14:02.292 --> 14:04.209
It means a lot. It really does.

14:12.751 --> 14:15.417
KENNY G: Yeah, look at that.
There I am on the stairs.

14:16.959 --> 14:19.584
♪ (SOFT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

14:23.292 --> 14:24.751
Unofficially, Seattle is
considered

14:24.834 --> 14:27.209
to be the jazz capital
of the northwest.

14:27.292 --> 14:29.667
Officially, the Franklin
High School Jazz Lab

14:29.751 --> 14:31.918
is the grand champion
of high school bands

14:32.000 --> 14:33.500
for the west coast.

14:33.584 --> 14:35.876
<i>This 18-piece ensemble
has pushed itself</i>

14:36.000 --> 14:37.959
<i>to an incredible list
of achievements.</i>

14:38.042 --> 14:40.459
This is the Franklin Jazz Lab.

14:40.542 --> 14:43.876
♪ (UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

14:43.959 --> 14:47.125
KENNY G:<i> The Jazz Lab.</i>
<i>Loved it, just loved it.</i>

14:47.209 --> 14:50.500
<i>And we had a composer
in residence.</i>

14:50.584 --> 14:51.959
<i>This guy, Jim Gardiner.</i>

14:52.042 --> 14:53.167
<i>And all the guys in the band,</i>

14:53.250 --> 14:54.959
we all really loved
Jim Gardiner.

14:55.042 --> 14:56.876
When you're teaching
somebody,

14:56.959 --> 14:59.459
you really don't know
if you're gonna be

14:59.542 --> 15:02.584
affecting them, that makes them
do something

15:02.667 --> 15:04.500
for the rest of their life.

15:04.584 --> 15:07.709
<i>Kenny was quiet, shy,</i>

15:07.792 --> 15:11.417
<i>and very, very smart.</i>

15:11.500 --> 15:12.876
He didn't have any girlfriends.

15:12.959 --> 15:15.834
The only girlfriend he had
was that new soprano sax.

15:15.918 --> 15:21.459
♪ (UPBEAT SAXOPHONE
NOTES PLAYING) ♪

15:21.542 --> 15:24.334
JAMES GARDINER:
<i>Kenny was an incredible reader.</i>

15:24.417 --> 15:25.667
<i>I mean, read anything.</i>

15:25.751 --> 15:28.167
So I would write some stuff
out for him freehand,

15:28.250 --> 15:29.417
and I'd pass it to him.

15:29.500 --> 15:31.626
Then all of a sudden...
(IMITATES SAX NOTES)

15:31.709 --> 15:33.709
And he played, these sight reads
and stuff.

15:33.792 --> 15:38.334
I said, "Okay, okay,
so let's move this up a notch."

15:38.417 --> 15:43.209
♪ ("UNTIL IT'S TIME
FOR YOU TO GO" PLAYING) ♪

15:43.292 --> 15:45.876
<i>There was an artist by
the name of Grover Washington.</i>

15:45.959 --> 15:47.751
And I had gotten the album,

15:47.834 --> 15:50.584
and I brought
the album to school

15:50.667 --> 15:52.959
and I gave it to Kenny and said,
you know,

15:53.042 --> 15:55.500
<i>"I think that you should
check this out."</i>

15:57.125 --> 15:59.792
KENNY G:<i> And that was what</i>
<i>really got me going,</i>

15:59.876 --> 16:01.709
<i>'cause his sound was
so beautiful to me.</i>

16:01.792 --> 16:03.792
<i>And I said, "I'm gonna sound
just like him."</i>

16:03.876 --> 16:05.125
<i>"That's my sound."</i>

16:06.083 --> 16:10.375
♪ (SONG CONTINUES) ♪

16:10.459 --> 16:13.542
KENNY G:<i> Every night,</i>
<i>I'd put on</i> Inner City Blues

16:13.626 --> 16:15.584
<i>and I would go to sleep
to that record.</i>

16:15.667 --> 16:18.918
<i>Every night, probably for
at least two and a half years</i>

16:19.000 --> 16:20.709
<i>of my high school life.</i>

16:20.792 --> 16:23.792
So, I tried to become
the white Grover Washington, Jr.

16:23.876 --> 16:25.500
And I tried really hard.

16:25.584 --> 16:28.417
♪ (UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

16:30.500 --> 16:32.083
<i>But every time I played
my saxophone,</i>

16:32.167 --> 16:34.292
<i>it just sounded like me,
it didn't sound like him.</i>

16:34.375 --> 16:36.292
And I was so frustrated.

16:36.375 --> 16:38.000
But, in the long run,

16:38.083 --> 16:39.584
it's good to have
your own sound.

16:42.667 --> 16:43.918
<i>The very good kids,</i>

16:44.000 --> 16:45.542
I would invite them to sit in,

16:45.626 --> 16:46.918
you know,
with my professional band.

16:47.000 --> 16:49.417
<i>And we had a concert
at the Opera House.</i>

16:49.500 --> 16:52.959
<i>So, I said to Kenny, "You get
to have a solo at this gig."</i>

16:56.375 --> 16:58.000
Kenny walks out
in front of the audience.

16:58.083 --> 17:00.751
He's supposed to do a cadenza,
like... (IMITATES SAX NOTES)

17:00.834 --> 17:03.209
You know, with the stuff
you hear him doing today, right?

17:03.292 --> 17:07.542
So instead of doing that,
Kenny decides to hold a note.

17:07.626 --> 17:09.626
♪ (SUSTAINED SAX NOTE PLAYING) ♪

17:09.709 --> 17:11.167
<i>Not just a note.</i>

17:11.250 --> 17:15.042
<i>I mean, he took Mother Earth
and was holding a note.</i>

17:15.125 --> 17:18.709
And he's holding a note
for ten minutes.

17:18.792 --> 17:24.334
(IMITATES SUSTAINED SAX NOTE)

17:24.417 --> 17:26.876
I looked over my shoulder,
imagine Kenny's playing
over here.

17:26.959 --> 17:30.334
And all of a sudden, a light
is shining on this kid.

17:30.417 --> 17:32.876
<i>I'm going-- And a big old light.
Whoo!</i>

17:32.959 --> 17:35.292
I'm going, "What the hell?"
and stuff.

17:35.375 --> 17:36.834
You know, and all of sudden
he holds that--

17:36.918 --> 17:38.250
Standing ovation.

17:38.334 --> 17:40.334
<i>-Whoo! My God.</i>
-(AUDIENCE CHEERING FAINTLY)

17:41.918 --> 17:44.834
<i>And that was,
at that particular moment,</i>

17:44.918 --> 17:46.709
<i>when the gates of heaven
opened up</i>

17:46.792 --> 17:49.542
<i>and gave Kenny
the other elements</i>

17:49.626 --> 17:50.959
<i>that he was searching for,</i>

17:51.042 --> 17:53.667
which is his soul
with his instrument.

17:54.417 --> 17:55.584
<i>That was the moment</i>

17:55.667 --> 17:58.959
<i>little Kenny Gorelick
became the G-Man.</i>

18:00.667 --> 18:05.542
(AUDIENCE CHEERING, APPLAUDING)

18:09.876 --> 18:13.167
♪ (SOFT PIANO MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

18:18.250 --> 18:24.459
♪ (SENTIMENTAL NOTES PLAY) ♪

20:13.042 --> 20:17.667
(AUDIENCE CHEERS, APPLAUDS)

20:17.751 --> 20:21.834
(EMERGENCY SIREN
BLARING IN DISTANCE)

20:21.918 --> 20:24.959
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

20:27.584 --> 20:29.876
FAN:<i> I have Alexa in my house,</i>

20:29.959 --> 20:33.209
and every morning I wake up
at about 7:00.

20:33.292 --> 20:34.834
And before I make my coffee,

20:34.918 --> 20:38.542
I always ask Alexa
to play Kenny G.

20:38.626 --> 20:41.584
It just, like, makes me feel,
you know, calm.

20:41.667 --> 20:43.792
You know? It calms me out,
you know?

20:43.876 --> 20:47.584
I had a big crush on him
since I was 12,

20:47.667 --> 20:50.417
and my dad introduced me to him.

20:50.500 --> 20:52.125
-It's from our childhood.
-Yeah.

20:52.209 --> 20:53.626
Our parents listened to Kenny G.

20:53.709 --> 20:57.292
And I don't know how we ended
up finding the tickets,

20:57.375 --> 20:59.334
but we're like,
"Oh, shit, do you want to go?"

20:59.417 --> 21:00.751
-Yes, we do. Yes.
-(CHUCKLES)

21:02.626 --> 21:06.751
(IN SPANISH)

21:19.083 --> 21:20.584
He makes playing an instrument
really cool,

21:20.667 --> 21:23.542
so growing up, when we were
forced to play instruments

21:23.626 --> 21:26.125
and, you know, it wasn't
the coolest thing to do.

21:26.209 --> 21:27.459
He made it cool.

21:27.542 --> 21:29.459
-There's no one like him.
-We love the show.

21:29.542 --> 21:31.751
I've been listening to him
since I was a baby.

21:31.834 --> 21:33.584
Thirty-five years,
because of her.

21:33.667 --> 21:34.709
Yes.

21:34.792 --> 21:36.709
It always makes me angry
that people, you know,

21:36.792 --> 21:39.542
sometimes mock him, sort of,

21:39.626 --> 21:41.375
because, you know,
they call it easy listening.

21:41.459 --> 21:44.167
But he's a really serious,
excellent musician.

21:44.250 --> 21:47.751
-I mean, they wish they'd have
the success that he has...
-Yeah, right.

21:47.834 --> 21:50.500
-Right exactly.
-...in terms of instrumental
records.

21:50.584 --> 21:52.292
Right, isn't he
the world's leading...?

21:52.375 --> 21:55.250
Instrumental artist,
I'm pretty sure, so...

21:55.334 --> 21:57.042
Kenny's got a wide range
of styles.

21:57.125 --> 21:58.918
He plays everything.

21:59.000 --> 22:01.042
Salsa, jazz,
he plays everything.

22:01.125 --> 22:04.334
Pop. He's the number one
instrumentalist in the world.

22:04.417 --> 22:07.876
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

22:07.959 --> 22:14.751
♪ (MELODIC SAXOPHONE
MUSIC PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS) ♪

22:17.375 --> 22:19.125
♪ (MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

22:20.834 --> 22:22.792
-♪ (MUSIC STOPS) ♪
-KENNY G: So, I'll do
the same thing again.

22:22.876 --> 22:24.584
<i>One thing that's interesting
is that</i>

22:24.667 --> 22:27.209
when people hear me play live,

22:27.292 --> 22:28.334
they're usually hearing it

22:28.417 --> 22:30.792
through a microphone
and speakers.

22:31.417 --> 22:32.500
But here in the studio,

22:32.584 --> 22:35.083
if I were to record
my saxophone,

22:35.167 --> 22:37.125
you would hear it sounding like
this in the room,

22:37.209 --> 22:39.751
and then I'll turn it on and see
what it really sounds like.

22:39.834 --> 22:44.626
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

22:58.375 --> 23:00.792
Sounds pretty nice,
but when we actually hear

23:00.876 --> 23:02.500
what it will sound like
on the recording,

23:02.584 --> 23:04.751
it adds all the beauty,
and I'll show you what we do.

23:04.834 --> 23:08.626
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS) ♪

23:19.334 --> 23:21.667
So that sounds all so beautiful.

23:21.751 --> 23:26.209
Usually the same three or four
reverbs in combination...

23:26.292 --> 23:27.918
-KENNY G: Yeah.
-...to make the whole sound.

23:28.000 --> 23:30.751
Without being egotistical
and no conceit here,

23:30.834 --> 23:33.500
when I hear my sax recorded,

23:33.584 --> 23:35.542
like when I give it
my stamp of approval,

23:35.626 --> 23:38.417
I sit back and go,
"That's fucking beautiful."

23:38.500 --> 23:40.000
I just say it.

23:40.083 --> 23:45.709
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

23:47.834 --> 23:49.042
Cool.

23:49.125 --> 23:51.709
I can just select this note
right here...

23:51.792 --> 23:52.876
right there.

23:52.959 --> 23:54.250
If I press record,

23:54.334 --> 23:56.000
I will go in at the beginning
of that note,

23:56.083 --> 23:57.250
out to the end of that note.

23:57.334 --> 23:58.667
So let's hear
how it sounds now.

23:58.751 --> 24:04.167
♪ (MELODIC SAXOPHONE
MUSIC PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS) ♪

24:04.250 --> 24:07.125
I'm going to record myself
playing that note again.

24:07.209 --> 24:08.292
So watch this.

24:09.375 --> 24:13.000
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

24:13.083 --> 24:14.709
Now let's see
what it sounds like.

24:14.792 --> 24:16.918
You can see how seamless
this recording is.

24:17.000 --> 24:20.334
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS) ♪

24:20.417 --> 24:22.209
You can't tell that
there's even an edit in there.

24:22.292 --> 24:25.375
Perfect. Okay, so,
how many edits are there?

24:25.459 --> 24:27.042
Well, let's see.
There's an edit.

24:27.125 --> 24:28.375
There's one right there.
There's one right there.

24:28.459 --> 24:30.042
There's another right there.
There's one right there.

24:30.125 --> 24:31.125
There's one right there.

24:31.209 --> 24:33.250
This section right here
was an edit.

24:33.334 --> 24:35.042
This little part
of this note was.

24:35.125 --> 24:36.459
This section was an edit.

24:36.542 --> 24:39.375
-PENNY: That's part of a note?
-Part of a note, right there.

24:39.459 --> 24:40.876
I mean, it may look like
it's sterile,

24:40.959 --> 24:42.500
the way we do it, but it's not.

24:42.584 --> 24:43.834
It's actually-- It's from here.

24:43.918 --> 24:46.500
It's like, "Why doesn't that
sound right to me?"

24:46.584 --> 24:48.000
"Hmm, it's just that one note."

24:48.083 --> 24:49.375
So when you fix that one note,

24:49.459 --> 24:52.959
you're not making
like a laboratory thing,

24:53.042 --> 24:54.334
and it doesn't take away
the feeling.

24:54.417 --> 24:56.375
It adds to it.
That's how I do it.

24:56.459 --> 24:58.500
Some people just wanna do
a take from start to finish,

24:58.584 --> 25:02.209
and they believe that
a live take is the way to go.

25:02.292 --> 25:03.459
For me...

25:04.834 --> 25:06.918
it's-- I'm gonna hear it
forever.

25:07.000 --> 25:09.292
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

25:09.375 --> 25:12.292
<i>This album we've been
working on about two years now.</i>

25:12.375 --> 25:15.584
<i>The album is called</i>
New Standards

25:15.667 --> 25:18.792
<i>because I like
old jazz standards.</i>

25:18.876 --> 25:22.125
And these standards have been
played so many times.

25:22.209 --> 25:25.042
So, I don't want to do
an album of those standards.

25:25.125 --> 25:27.209
I want to do an album
that sounds like

25:27.292 --> 25:31.334
I'm doing those standards,
but they're my new creations.

25:31.417 --> 25:32.876
So it's called<i> New Standards.</i>

25:32.959 --> 25:34.459
This is the inspiration, right?

25:34.542 --> 25:38.250
Because there's Charlie Parker,
that's Dizzy Gillespie.

25:38.334 --> 25:41.292
I'm pretty sure
that is Dexter Gordon.

25:42.417 --> 25:44.417
And then, this keyboard player,

25:44.500 --> 25:46.751
gosh, I'm not 100 percent sure
who that is.

25:49.375 --> 25:51.792
-PRODUCER:
It's Monk with the hat.
-It is Monk!

25:51.876 --> 25:54.417
-It is Monk!
-Yes. (CHUCKLES)

25:54.500 --> 25:56.542
Perfect. That's great.

25:58.042 --> 26:02.918
This is the paradox
of Kenny G's musical world.

26:03.000 --> 26:06.083
It does come from a tradition.

26:06.167 --> 26:08.334
♪ (TRADITIONAL
JAZZ MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

26:15.167 --> 26:16.751
<i>And yet, Kenny G's music</i>

26:16.834 --> 26:21.584
seems to want to have
nothing to do with a past.

26:21.667 --> 26:25.459
♪ (SMOOTH JAZZ PLAYING) ♪

26:25.542 --> 26:27.834
<i>Jazz has been
a chronological development.</i>

26:27.918 --> 26:31.167
And each stage
of its development

26:31.250 --> 26:34.834
has built on what went before.

26:34.918 --> 26:40.209
♪ (UPBEAT JAZZ PLAYING) ♪

26:40.292 --> 26:41.500
BEN:<i> What is jazz?</i>

26:41.584 --> 26:43.334
<i>Well, it's a music that has
this element</i>

26:43.417 --> 26:45.167
and that element. Sure, fine.

26:45.250 --> 26:47.626
♪ (TRUMPET SOLO PLAYS) ♪

26:47.709 --> 26:50.125
BEN:<i> But also, way up</i>
<i>on the list of things</i>

26:50.209 --> 26:51.626
<i>that are central to jazz
is the fact</i>

26:51.709 --> 26:53.918
<i>that it's a hundred-year
continuity.</i>

26:54.000 --> 26:56.459
♪ (JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

26:56.542 --> 26:58.292
People playing jazz currently

26:58.375 --> 26:59.876
are always in a kind of dialogue

26:59.959 --> 27:02.626
with people who played jazz
50 years ago or whatever.

27:07.792 --> 27:09.375
<i>In the music of Kenny G,</i>

27:09.459 --> 27:12.876
that continuity... is absent.

27:12.959 --> 27:15.042
I'm from Seattle,
and I live in a musical vacuum.

27:15.125 --> 27:18.000
I don't really listen
to much music,
I don't read the paper,

27:18.083 --> 27:20.334
I don't read magazines,
I don't watch the news.

27:20.417 --> 27:21.876
So I don't really know
what's happening.

27:21.959 --> 27:24.626
INTERVIEWER: Are you influenced
by the great saxophonists
of the--

27:24.709 --> 27:25.918
You know, we've had so many.

27:26.000 --> 27:27.792
I think I would say
I was influenced--

27:27.876 --> 27:31.000
-Or is that more of a jazz...?
-Well, it's real jazz sound,

27:31.083 --> 27:32.834
but it's the technique of it.

27:32.918 --> 27:34.792
The John Coltrane
and the Charlie Parker,

27:34.876 --> 27:36.292
I mean, their technique
was phenomenal.

27:36.375 --> 27:38.417
But that music was never
heartfelt for me,

27:38.500 --> 27:40.000
so when I went out
and gigged,

27:40.083 --> 27:42.292
it wasn't anything
that I wanted to emulate.

27:42.375 --> 27:44.167
You know, Kenny G
is playing music

27:44.250 --> 27:48.375
that is sort of related to jazz
but isn't jazz.

27:48.459 --> 27:51.751
Jazz is a very complicated
art form,

27:51.834 --> 27:54.042
and to master bebop harmony,

27:54.125 --> 27:56.083
and let's not even go
into what that is.

27:56.167 --> 27:58.083
I mean, it's really like
getting-- it's like getting

27:58.167 --> 28:00.209
a PhD in mathematics,
in a lot of ways.

28:00.292 --> 28:03.083
It is not the same
as just picking up your horn

28:03.167 --> 28:04.584
and playing what you feel.

28:04.667 --> 28:06.876
♪ (UPBEAT JAZZ PLAYING) ♪

28:11.626 --> 28:13.751
<i>Part of what makes jazz
interesting</i>

28:13.834 --> 28:15.459
<i>is this sense of
call and response</i>

28:15.542 --> 28:17.083
<i>and dialogue
among the musicians.</i>

28:23.125 --> 28:26.167
<i>And what you hear
in Kenny G's music</i>

28:26.250 --> 28:28.542
is no conversation at all.

28:28.626 --> 28:31.042
This is a solo project.

28:31.125 --> 28:33.751
This is not sex.
This is masturbation.

28:33.834 --> 28:38.167
♪ (SAXOPHONE PLAYING) ♪

28:38.250 --> 28:41.167
CHRIS:<i> The model that he's using</i>
<i>is not a jazz model</i>

28:41.250 --> 28:43.626
<i>where everybody gets to have
a kind of an equal voice</i>

28:43.709 --> 28:45.459
<i>within the jazz unit.</i>

28:45.542 --> 28:48.918
It's much more of a pop act,
where he is the star.

28:53.626 --> 28:55.876
KENNY G:<i> Somebody asked me,</i>
<i>"What kind of music do you do?"</i>

28:55.959 --> 28:57.584
<i>"Uh, I play sax."
"Well, what kind?"</i>

28:57.667 --> 28:59.626
<i>"It's instrumental music."
"Well, is it jazz?"</i>

28:59.709 --> 29:02.500
<i>I don't know. You might think
it might be jazz.</i>

29:02.584 --> 29:04.417
"Well, is it pop?"
I don't know.

29:04.500 --> 29:06.000
You might think
it might be pop.

29:06.876 --> 29:08.667
Those labels are tricky.

29:09.834 --> 29:12.918
I mean, my songs were played
on pop radio.

29:13.000 --> 29:16.375
They were played on jazz radio.
They were played on R&B radio.

29:16.459 --> 29:17.709
Am I an R&B artist?

29:18.792 --> 29:21.250
Am I a pop artist?
Am I a jazz artist?

29:21.334 --> 29:23.918
I think maybe the answer is yes,
just to everything.

29:24.000 --> 29:27.083
Now that we're taking a break,
tell me, how is it going?

29:27.167 --> 29:28.334
PENNY: It's going great!

29:28.417 --> 29:30.334
I mean, seriously,
are you getting what you want?

29:30.417 --> 29:31.834
-Yes!
-Am I talking too long?

29:31.918 --> 29:33.417
-No!
-Am I animated enough?

29:33.500 --> 29:34.792
Am I too animated?

29:34.876 --> 29:36.709
That's my problem, is that
I always wanna be too good

29:36.792 --> 29:39.000
-at everything, and so--
-I think you're doing great.

29:39.083 --> 29:40.542
I want to be the best.
See, my problem is,

29:40.626 --> 29:43.167
I wanna be the best interview
you've ever had.

29:43.250 --> 29:45.751
And if that means sitting here
for 12 hours

29:45.834 --> 29:47.542
and not eating or drinking,

29:47.626 --> 29:48.918
I'll do it.
That's my problem.

29:49.000 --> 29:51.250
So I would give you
whatever you want,

29:51.334 --> 29:52.792
-as long as you want.
-We're doing great.

29:52.876 --> 29:54.000
Okay, good.

29:57.167 --> 30:00.042
KENNY G: There's a picture of me
as a baby, this one, up there.

30:00.125 --> 30:01.959
That's me as a little baby.

30:02.042 --> 30:03.292
<i>I was a very happy baby.</i>

30:03.375 --> 30:05.876
<i>I've been a happy kid
my whole life.</i>

30:05.959 --> 30:07.209
<i>I really have.</i>

30:07.292 --> 30:09.709
I might worry,
or we call it kvetching.

30:09.792 --> 30:12.125
You know, it's a Jewish word
called kvetching.

30:12.209 --> 30:15.083
It's like, okay, you might be
kind of complaining

30:15.167 --> 30:16.876
about this and that,
but it doesn't last,

30:16.959 --> 30:19.417
it just kind of... (WHISTLES)
...and I'm back to normal.

30:19.500 --> 30:21.792
Oh, there's my grandpa.
Lived to 103.

30:21.876 --> 30:24.500
And he was always happy.
Never complained.

30:24.584 --> 30:26.876
Like my father, my father
never complains either.

30:26.959 --> 30:28.792
And my dad now is 98.

30:29.876 --> 30:31.500
<i>My dad started off as a plumber,</i>

30:31.584 --> 30:34.834
<i>and then he created a wholesale
company for plumbing,</i>

30:34.918 --> 30:38.751
<i>hardware stuff
called Thrifty Supply Company.</i>

30:38.834 --> 30:40.584
It was always kind of expected

30:40.667 --> 30:44.876
that I would end up working
at Thrifty Supply.

30:44.959 --> 30:48.417
<i>I graduated from college,
and we had a talk.</i>

30:48.500 --> 30:50.542
And I said, "Dad, listen...

30:50.626 --> 30:52.250
I've done a bunch of gigs."

30:52.334 --> 30:54.918
♪ ("SOMEBODY'S GONNA BURN YA" BY
COLD, BOLD & TOGETHER PLAYING) ♪

30:55.000 --> 30:57.459
<i>I played for different people
that would come to town.</i>

30:57.542 --> 30:59.125
<i>Like, Sammy Davis Jr.</i>

30:59.209 --> 31:01.375
<i>So, I played
with Sammy Davis Jr.</i>

31:01.459 --> 31:03.042
<i>Liberace. I played
with Liberace.</i>

31:03.125 --> 31:05.834
<i>The Ringling Bros. Circus
would come to Seattle,</i>

31:05.918 --> 31:08.709
<i>I'm in the Ringling Bros.
Circus band.</i>

31:08.792 --> 31:12.334
<i>I'm also with an R&B band,
Cold, Bold & Together.</i>

31:12.417 --> 31:15.000
<i>So I'm becoming well known
in Seattle</i>

31:15.083 --> 31:17.042
<i>as a guy that can play.</i>

31:17.125 --> 31:19.667
"Dad, I'd really like to give
this a couple more years."

31:19.751 --> 31:23.626
"And if nothing works out,
I'll come to Thrifty."

31:25.459 --> 31:27.959
He says, "No problem."
I said, "Great."

31:28.042 --> 31:30.209
One, two, three.

31:30.292 --> 31:31.959
♪ (UPBEAT SAXOPHONE
NOTES PLAYING) ♪

31:32.042 --> 31:33.417
<i>In Portland, Oregon,</i>

31:33.500 --> 31:36.876
<i>this guy named Jeff Lorber
is putting together his band.</i>

31:38.000 --> 31:39.250
<i>So I drive down, audition,</i>

31:39.334 --> 31:40.250
I get the gig,

31:40.334 --> 31:42.250
and now I'm playing
with Jeff Lorber.

31:42.334 --> 31:48.792
♪ (SAXOPHONE SOLO PLAYING) ♪

31:54.834 --> 31:57.417
<i>Jeff Lorber's record company,
Arista Records,</i>

31:57.500 --> 31:58.918
<i>and the big man there,
Clive Davis,</i>

31:59.042 --> 32:01.167
<i>would come down
to see Jeff Lorber play.</i>

32:01.250 --> 32:04.083
So Clive Davis saw me play
many times.

32:04.167 --> 32:05.626
And after five years

32:05.709 --> 32:08.042
and watching the audience
react to my playing,

32:08.876 --> 32:10.459
which was positive,

32:10.542 --> 32:12.083
he said to me one day,

32:12.167 --> 32:14.292
"Would you like to have
your own record deal?"

32:14.375 --> 32:16.500
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

32:16.584 --> 32:19.334
NARRATOR:<i> The resident genius</i>
<i>of Arista Records,</i>

32:19.417 --> 32:21.000
<i>Mr. Clive Davis.</i>

32:21.083 --> 32:24.209
REPORTER:<i> Davis's track record</i>
<i>of success began in 1967.</i>

32:24.292 --> 32:26.626
<i>Back then as president
of CBS Records,</i>

32:26.709 --> 32:28.209
<i>he sensed a revolution in music</i>

32:28.292 --> 32:31.250
<i>and signed up artists
such as Santana, Janis Joplin,</i>

32:31.334 --> 32:33.918
<i>Blood, Sweat & Tears,
and Chicago.</i>

32:34.000 --> 32:37.125
CLIVE DAVIS:
<i>I went to see a tour performance</i>

32:37.209 --> 32:40.792
of the Jeff Lorber group. And...

32:40.876 --> 32:45.584
there was Kenny, standing up
and doing his magic.

32:45.667 --> 32:48.417
<i>I was very impressed.</i>

32:48.500 --> 32:53.250
<i>He had a very natural gift
of relating to the audience.</i>

32:53.334 --> 32:54.834
♪ (FAST SAXOPHONE NOTES
PLAYING) ♪

32:54.918 --> 32:57.667
KENNY G:<i> Clive Davis,</i>
<i>he's just a music man.</i>

32:57.751 --> 32:59.459
<i>It's a puzzle, I think, to him.</i>

32:59.542 --> 33:00.876
He puts pieces together.

33:00.959 --> 33:02.042
He sees it

33:02.125 --> 33:04.417
and he can put it together.
Like he's-- for example,

33:05.584 --> 33:08.167
<i>he would find
a Whitney Houston</i>

33:08.250 --> 33:09.459
<i>and then he would think,</i>

33:09.542 --> 33:10.876
"Who should write
the songs for her?"

33:10.959 --> 33:12.334
And then he puts
the people together,

33:12.417 --> 33:14.167
<i>and then he puts
the producers together,</i>

33:14.250 --> 33:15.709
<i>and they come out
with this record.</i>

33:15.792 --> 33:18.792
<i>And, of course, she becomes
an international superstar.</i>

33:18.876 --> 33:23.542
♪ ("SAVING ALL MY LOVE FOR YOU"
BY WHITNEY HOUSTON PLAYING) ♪

33:23.626 --> 33:26.417
JASON:<i> Popular music</i>
<i>doesn't just show up.</i>

33:26.500 --> 33:28.959
<i>It's constructed, it's mediated.</i>

33:29.042 --> 33:32.167
Often, we make assessments
or evaluations

33:32.250 --> 33:35.125
about what an artist has done,
or what their intentions are.

33:35.209 --> 33:38.250
But we fail to realize
that those artistic choices

33:38.334 --> 33:41.417
are being made
in a much larger context.

33:41.500 --> 33:44.876
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

33:44.959 --> 33:47.542
<i>So to talk about
Kenny G properly,</i>

33:47.626 --> 33:50.500
you have to talk about
the business aspect.

33:50.584 --> 33:53.042
♪ ("MERCY MERCY MERCY"
PLAYING) ♪

33:53.125 --> 33:56.042
KENNY G:<i> My first album</i>
<i>was produced by Jeff Lorber.</i>

33:56.125 --> 33:58.209
<i>Clive Davis is basically saying,</i>

33:58.292 --> 33:59.709
<i>"We're gonna have
the Jeff Lorber sound,</i>

33:59.792 --> 34:02.042
<i>but now it's just
gonna feature you."</i>

34:02.125 --> 34:04.500
It's the one where I look like
Richard Simmons.

34:06.125 --> 34:10.334
<i>That one did not so great.
Sold about 40,000 records.</i>

34:10.417 --> 34:13.375
JASON:<i> Clive Davis's approach</i>
<i>was to put an album out</i>

34:13.459 --> 34:14.959
<i>and if it didn't quite hit,</i>

34:15.042 --> 34:17.584
you would re-jigger it
a little bit,

34:17.667 --> 34:20.834
<i>change the sounds,
alter the marketing.</i>

34:22.000 --> 34:24.250
CLIVE:<i> It was dawning on me</i>

34:24.334 --> 34:27.459
<i>that although he's a soloist</i>

34:27.542 --> 34:29.584
in what was a jazz band,

34:29.667 --> 34:33.042
that his primary appeal

34:33.709 --> 34:34.918
would really be pop.

34:35.000 --> 34:37.792
So they said, "We'll have you
work with Kashif."

34:37.876 --> 34:41.584
♪ ("STONE LOVE"
BY KASHIF PLAYING) ♪

34:41.667 --> 34:45.417
JASON:<i> Kashif was a legendary</i>
<i>R&B performer,</i>

34:45.500 --> 34:48.000
<i>producer, a songwriter.</i>

34:48.083 --> 34:50.459
They were interested in results
and getting hits.

34:50.542 --> 34:52.334
Kashif was the hot producer
at the time.

34:52.417 --> 34:56.125
He had a song out
with Evelyn "Champagne" King.

34:56.209 --> 34:57.918
<i>♪ Love come down ♪</i>

34:58.000 --> 35:02.375
<i>♪ Ooh, you make my love
Come down ♪</i>

35:04.209 --> 35:05.500
He did that song.

35:05.584 --> 35:06.918
And that was huge.

35:07.000 --> 35:09.626
Clive Davis and Arista
were trying to find the formula

35:09.709 --> 35:10.959
that would work,

35:11.042 --> 35:13.000
and they were mercenaries

35:13.083 --> 35:14.667
at doing that,
whatever it took.

35:16.292 --> 35:17.500
♪ ("HI, HOW YA DOIN'?"
PLAYING) ♪

35:17.584 --> 35:19.626
PENNY:<i> I want to talk</i>
<i>about your first music video.</i>

35:19.709 --> 35:21.542
-KENNY G:<i> That's awful.</i>
<i>-I think it's great.</i>

35:21.626 --> 35:22.959
KENNY G:
<i>If you show that in this film,</i>

35:23.042 --> 35:24.375
I'm going to boycott
the premiere.

35:24.459 --> 35:25.876
(PENNY LAUGHING)

35:25.959 --> 35:29.000
PENNY: Okay, if I show it,
it will be in the context

35:29.083 --> 35:31.459
of you saying
how you feel about it.

35:31.542 --> 35:32.667
-Good, I'm glad.
-Okay.

35:32.751 --> 35:35.876
It's just ridiculous,
that thing.

35:35.959 --> 35:38.584
♪ (SONG CONTINUES) ♪

35:40.667 --> 35:42.709
<i>The philosophy
of the record company was,</i>

35:42.792 --> 35:44.876
<i>there's no format
for instrumentals,</i>

35:44.959 --> 35:46.292
<i>so we're gonna do vocal songs.</i>

35:46.375 --> 35:48.792
That's what is going to get
radio airplay.

35:48.876 --> 35:50.459
You're going to play
the sax solo.

35:50.542 --> 35:52.459
They'll discover you
through this.

35:54.292 --> 35:56.500
<i>And I thought,
"That sounds awful."</i>

35:57.584 --> 35:58.751
<i>People are gonna be tricked</i>

35:58.834 --> 36:00.250
<i>into thinking
that I'm the singer,</i>

36:00.334 --> 36:02.375
<i>and who knows
if they're gonna like sax stuff?</i>

36:03.459 --> 36:06.167
Can't we just put out
instrumental music?

36:06.250 --> 36:07.542
"Nope, not gonna to work."

36:09.417 --> 36:11.626
<i>There's a point where
I'm break-dancing on the floor</i>

36:11.709 --> 36:15.209
<i>like some weird, like, rotating.
And then I come up,</i>

36:15.292 --> 36:17.417
<i>and I start playing my sax solo.</i>

36:17.500 --> 36:20.667
♪ (SAXOPHONE SOLO PLAYING) ♪

36:20.751 --> 36:22.667
<i>And that is supposed to change
everybody's mind.</i>

36:22.751 --> 36:25.542
Like, oh, all of a sudden,
"Oh, he's the artist?" Yeah.

36:26.334 --> 36:27.375
<i>Never worked.</i>

36:29.042 --> 36:30.918
By the way, have you ever
seen the single

36:31.000 --> 36:32.709
for "Hi, How Ya Doin'?"

36:32.792 --> 36:35.876
The single shows
a "silhouette" of a guy.

36:35.959 --> 36:38.834
<i>You can't tell
whether he's white or Black.</i>

36:38.918 --> 36:42.709
<i>At that time, the most success
we have is in Black radio.</i>

36:42.792 --> 36:44.083
And they wanted to make sure

36:44.167 --> 36:46.167
<i>that people didn't know I was
white.</i>

36:46.250 --> 36:48.500
I thought they were
a bunch of shenanigans.

36:48.584 --> 36:50.626
Like, you ever seen the cover
of<i> G Force?</i>

36:50.709 --> 36:51.751
<i>Same thing.</i>

36:51.834 --> 36:53.125
<i>But that record did pretty well.</i>

36:53.209 --> 36:55.292
<i>I think it sold, like,
200,000 records.</i>

36:55.375 --> 36:56.584
<i>So me and Kashif</i>

36:56.667 --> 36:58.000
<i>were gonna make
another record together.</i>

36:58.083 --> 37:00.250
♪ ("LOVE ON THE RISE" PLAYING) ♪

37:01.292 --> 37:03.250
<i>It's called</i> Gravity.

37:03.334 --> 37:07.417
<i>I hated that record. Hated it.
And it didn't sell well.</i>

37:07.500 --> 37:09.626
<i>Which I was actually
kind of happy about.</i>

37:09.709 --> 37:12.626
I thought, "I don't want
to do any of this again."

37:12.709 --> 37:14.626
<i>I want to do my own kind
of music.</i>

37:18.167 --> 37:19.500
<i>So, 1986,</i>

37:19.584 --> 37:21.250
the fourth record comes,

37:21.334 --> 37:24.209
and I had written
a whole bunch of instrumentals.

37:24.292 --> 37:27.792
<i>So I sent them
to the guys at Arista Records,</i>

37:27.876 --> 37:30.334
They go, "Eh, yeah,
these are all right, but

37:30.417 --> 37:31.834
we're looking for songs

37:31.918 --> 37:35.626
that the 15-year-old kids
in the ghetto can groove to."

37:36.500 --> 37:38.334
And I said...

37:38.417 --> 37:41.709
"You know I'm a Jewish
sax player from Seattle."

37:41.792 --> 37:43.167
"You realize that, right?"

37:43.250 --> 37:45.834
I said, "You know what?
I quit."

37:45.918 --> 37:48.792
"I quit. You guys need
to drop me from the label."

37:48.876 --> 37:50.209
He goes, "What are you
talking about?"

37:50.292 --> 37:53.000
I said,
"What am I talking about?"

37:53.083 --> 37:54.459
"What do I know

37:54.542 --> 37:56.125
about 15-year-old
kids in the ghetto?"

37:56.209 --> 37:58.459
"What do you mean?
We need to write songs

37:58.542 --> 38:00.500
they can groove to, from me?"

38:00.584 --> 38:02.459
"I have no idea
what you're talking about."

38:02.542 --> 38:06.042
So he goes,
"Look, look, before..."

38:06.125 --> 38:07.626
"Well, do me a favor."

38:07.709 --> 38:09.167
"There's a Junior Walker
song..."

38:09.250 --> 38:11.459
♪ ("WHAT DOES IT TAKE" BY
JR. WALKER & THE ALL STARS
PLAYING) ♪

38:11.542 --> 38:13.125
<i>"...and we think
that if you do a redo,</i>

38:13.209 --> 38:14.584
<i>it could be really good."</i>

38:16.125 --> 38:18.584
<i>"Has vocals, but it's really
a sax song."</i>

38:20.375 --> 38:22.584
<i>So I listened to the song
and I went,</i>

38:22.667 --> 38:24.959
"Okay, that seems like
a good compromise."

38:25.709 --> 38:27.292
♪ (SONG CONTINUES) ♪

38:28.209 --> 38:29.584
<i>Record comes out.</i>

38:29.667 --> 38:31.209
<i>It's kind of a hit.</i>

38:31.292 --> 38:33.584
<i>And we're at 300,000 records.</i>

38:33.667 --> 38:34.792
That's good for me.

38:34.876 --> 38:37.000
♪ ("WHAT DOES IT TAKE"
PLAYING) ♪

38:37.083 --> 38:40.751
<i>I got a call
from my manager who said,</i>

38:40.834 --> 38:43.375
<i>"I'm gonna see if I can
get you on Johnny Carson."</i>

38:45.042 --> 38:47.834
So exciting. So I--
So I get the shot.

38:47.918 --> 38:50.334
ANNOUNCER:<i> From Hollywood,</i>

38:50.417 --> 38:52.125
The Tonight Show,<i> starring...</i>

38:52.209 --> 38:54.292
<i>And they say,
"You're gonna do your single,</i>

38:54.375 --> 38:56.125
'What Does It Take
(To Win Your Love).'"

38:56.209 --> 38:57.667
"That's why you're here."

38:57.751 --> 39:00.209
"And then as
Johnny's going off air,

39:00.292 --> 39:01.959
you play-- We don't really care
what you play

39:02.042 --> 39:04.250
'cause we're signing off
anyway."

39:04.334 --> 39:06.459
I said, "Well, I'm gonna play
my song 'Songbird.'"

39:06.542 --> 39:07.584
"We don't care."

39:07.667 --> 39:08.667
Great young musician,

39:08.751 --> 39:09.918
plays great saxophone
in his group.

39:10.000 --> 39:11.459
-Kenny G is here tonight.
-(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS)

39:11.542 --> 39:12.959
Stay where you are...

39:13.042 --> 39:14.918
<i>So, I'm back there waiting
for the thing to happen,</i>

39:15.000 --> 39:17.334
and they come on the door,
knocking on the door.

39:17.417 --> 39:20.042
"Hey, Johnny's running late
tonight. Sorry."

39:20.125 --> 39:21.876
"We got to cut you down
to only one song,

39:21.959 --> 39:23.667
so come out and do your single."

39:23.751 --> 39:26.334
I said, "Okay, cool."
Door closes, I look to the guys.

39:26.417 --> 39:28.500
I go, "We're playing
'Songbird.'"

39:28.584 --> 39:31.542
I knew that I needed
to play that song.

39:31.626 --> 39:33.083
I wanted to play from my heart,

39:33.167 --> 39:35.918
I wanted people
to hear my music.

39:36.000 --> 39:38.959
Because "Songbird" was a song
that I just did all by myself.

39:39.042 --> 39:40.709
<i>I mean, I played
every instrument on the song,</i>

39:40.792 --> 39:42.959
<i>I recorded it in my own
little room.</i>

39:43.042 --> 39:44.209
I wanted that to be heard,

39:44.292 --> 39:47.626
not the single that the record
company came up with.

39:47.709 --> 39:49.167
<i>I want to play my instrumental.</i>

39:49.250 --> 39:50.959
Would you welcome, please,
Kenny G.

39:51.042 --> 39:52.876
-Kenny?
-(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS)

39:54.876 --> 39:56.751
KENNY G:<i> My band got so scared.</i>

39:56.834 --> 39:59.209
<i>I said,
"Don't screw me up here."</i>

39:59.292 --> 40:01.375
<i>"When the curtains go up,
start playing 'Songbird.'"</i>

40:01.459 --> 40:03.918
<i>"Don't start playing
the other song."</i>

40:04.000 --> 40:06.667
<i>"I'm on the Johnny Carson
show, tonight, now."</i>

40:06.751 --> 40:09.209
<i>"I am gonna play the song
I want to play."</i>

40:09.292 --> 40:14.334
♪ ("SONGBIRD" PLAYS) ♪

40:30.751 --> 40:33.459
<i>And the guy that hired us
is behind the cameras</i>

40:33.542 --> 40:36.500
<i>looking at me
like he wants to kill me.</i>

40:36.584 --> 40:39.500
<i>He's doing a lot of finger,
hand gestures to me</i>

40:39.584 --> 40:41.959
while I'm playing,
and not just this kind of stuff.

40:42.042 --> 40:45.709
We're talking about some
single-digit finger moves.

40:52.375 --> 40:57.292
<i>But that night, the wife
of the head of promotion,</i>

40:57.375 --> 41:00.000
<i>Donnie Ienner, says to him,</i>

41:00.083 --> 41:03.083
"Honey, now that's the kind of
music you guys should be doing."

41:03.167 --> 41:04.751
"That's beautiful."

41:06.959 --> 41:08.542
So Donnie Ienner
now walks into--

41:08.626 --> 41:10.334
Monday morning, into
Clive Davis's office

41:10.417 --> 41:12.500
and says, "Hey, Clive,
we got it all wrong."

41:12.584 --> 41:15.918
And so, Clive Davis
with his brilliance,

41:16.000 --> 41:19.375
no ego attached, goes,
"Boom, let's do the new single."

41:19.459 --> 41:22.083
And he starts writing letters
to the radio people.

41:22.167 --> 41:24.834
CLIVE:<i> I wrote</i>
<i>a personal letter,</i>

41:24.918 --> 41:26.667
which I had never done before,

41:26.751 --> 41:29.417
<i>to radio programmers</i>

41:29.500 --> 41:31.292
<i>of every genre.</i>

41:31.375 --> 41:33.959
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Start your day the easy way.</i>

41:34.042 --> 41:38.375
I said, "Look, I've given you
a lot of good music by now,

41:38.459 --> 41:41.459
and I need a favor here.

41:41.542 --> 41:42.876
<i>Play the record."</i>

41:44.167 --> 41:45.459
Three-twenty-three, this is...

41:45.542 --> 41:48.500
KENNY G:<i> Finally, one station,</i>
<i>KMEL, "Camel," puts it on.</i>

41:48.584 --> 41:50.918
<i>And it's 4:00 in the afternoon,
so it's drive time.</i>

41:51.000 --> 41:53.584
<i>This is a big deal.
Their phones light up.</i>

41:53.667 --> 41:55.250
<i>"We love it.
This song's beautiful."</i>

41:55.334 --> 41:57.042
"Why don't you play more songs
like that?"

41:57.125 --> 41:58.751
"We really like that,
who is that?"

41:58.834 --> 42:00.250
"I never heard a sound
like that before."

42:00.334 --> 42:02.375
<i>It's the demographic
they're looking for.</i>

42:02.459 --> 42:05.292
<i>I guess it's 25
to 35-year-old women.</i>

42:05.375 --> 42:10.542
So, he calls his contemporary
in Chicago at their station.

42:10.626 --> 42:12.709
And he calls Detroit,
and they call Atlanta,

42:12.792 --> 42:14.626
and they call Miami,
and they call Houston.

42:14.709 --> 42:16.876
And all of a sudden, these guys
are talking and saying,

42:16.959 --> 42:18.042
"Hey, we don't know why,

42:18.125 --> 42:21.667
but this instrumental
is working."

42:21.751 --> 42:24.334
And it becomes
a huge national hit song.

42:25.459 --> 42:32.250
♪ ("SONGBIRD" PLAYING) ♪

42:44.542 --> 42:47.083
I remember the first time
I heard "Songbird,"

42:47.167 --> 42:50.292
and I heard it on the radio.

42:50.375 --> 42:53.417
And it was just beautiful.

42:53.500 --> 42:55.542
That song is haunting.

42:55.626 --> 42:57.292
You know,
when Kenny came along

42:57.375 --> 42:59.542
there was just something
different about that song.

42:59.626 --> 43:02.417
The saxophone was mixed
more like a vocalist.

43:03.042 --> 43:04.083
It was more up front.

43:04.167 --> 43:06.083
And then the melody,
I mean, you know, that's one

43:06.167 --> 43:07.584
of the great melodies
of all time.

43:07.667 --> 43:11.125
Say the name Kenny Gorelick,
and many people will ask, who?

43:11.209 --> 43:14.375
<i>But say the name Kenny G,
and many will say "Songbird."</i>

43:14.459 --> 43:17.334
TV HOST:
<i>His current Arista album,</i>
Duotones,<i> is now double platinum</i>

43:17.417 --> 43:20.876
thanks to a top five
smash song called "Songbird."

43:20.959 --> 43:24.292
-Ladies and gentlemen, Kenny G.
-(AUDIENCE CHEERS)

43:24.375 --> 43:26.042
Please welcome Kenny G.

43:26.125 --> 43:27.417
(AUDIENCE CHEERS)

43:27.500 --> 43:29.209
There he is, Kenny G.

43:30.626 --> 43:33.167
OPRAH WINFREY:
<i>It's like you are talking to</i>

43:33.250 --> 43:36.000
and doing a few other things
with this instrument.

43:36.083 --> 43:38.083
-What-- When you... (CHUCKLES)
-Well...

43:38.167 --> 43:39.542
Well, I was gonna say--

43:39.626 --> 43:41.292
KENNY G:
I'm thinking about a few
other things when I'm playing.

43:41.375 --> 43:45.709
OPRAH:
It's like making love to this
instrument, it's incredible.

43:45.792 --> 43:48.083
TV HOST:
<i>Do you marvel at the breadth</i>
<i>of your popularity?</i>

43:48.167 --> 43:50.876
<i>That you've been able
to go outside the jazz world?</i>

43:50.959 --> 43:53.751
Well, it's so unusual
that pop stations

43:53.834 --> 43:55.500
have played my stuff.

43:55.584 --> 43:56.834
Why do you think that is?

43:57.292 --> 43:58.751
Clive Davis.

43:58.834 --> 44:01.167
KENNY G:<i> If it wasn't</i>
<i>for his personal letters</i>

44:01.250 --> 44:02.751
<i>to the radio programmers,</i>

44:02.834 --> 44:05.918
<i>that record "Songbird" probably
wouldn't have been a hit.</i>

44:07.584 --> 44:09.000
And then to finish the story,

44:09.083 --> 44:12.167
six months go by
and guess who calls?

44:12.250 --> 44:14.542
The guys from Johnny Carson.

44:14.626 --> 44:17.000
"We'd love to have you
back on the show." (CHUCKLES)

44:17.083 --> 44:19.042
"Please play 'Songbird.'"
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

44:20.417 --> 44:22.709
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

44:25.918 --> 44:29.500
It's not-- like, it's normally
a lot more neater than this,

44:29.584 --> 44:33.626
but I'm doing laundry right
now, so, you know...

44:33.709 --> 44:36.584
Nice golf shirt, see?
Nice perfect color.

44:36.667 --> 44:38.626
Look at these white pants.
They came out perfect.

44:38.709 --> 44:40.042
Look, there are no stains
in there.

44:40.125 --> 44:42.500
They were dirty before,
no stains, perfect.

44:43.792 --> 44:46.083
<i>Household chores are actually
a lot of fun for me.</i>

44:46.167 --> 44:48.250
We want to make sure
that's all mixed up.

44:48.334 --> 44:50.667
<i>It's like a detail thing.</i>

44:50.751 --> 44:52.542
<i>Like playing an instrument,
it's details</i>

44:52.626 --> 44:55.459
<i>that you get a reward
for doing them well.</i>

44:55.542 --> 44:58.417
I'm folding the top
under the bottom, see?

44:58.500 --> 45:00.334
That's the story of my life,
pretty much.

45:00.417 --> 45:02.709
<i>I'm into the details,
working hard,</i>

45:02.792 --> 45:04.209
<i>putting in the reps.</i>

45:04.292 --> 45:05.751
Timer, 20.

45:05.834 --> 45:08.959
And then reaping the reward of,
"Hey, I'm really good at this."

45:09.042 --> 45:11.417
"Hey, I'm really good at that.
Hey, I do this well."

45:11.500 --> 45:13.375
Mm, smells so good.

45:13.459 --> 45:16.626
Everything I try to get good
at, I've gotten good at.

45:16.709 --> 45:18.459
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

45:20.709 --> 45:23.792
-MAN: Well hit, man.
-KENNY G: Yes! On the green,
on the green...

45:23.876 --> 45:25.417
PENNY:<i> I wanna talk to you</i>
<i>about golf.</i>

45:25.500 --> 45:28.792
TV HOST:
Golf Digest<i> once called you</i>
<i>the best golfer in music.</i>

45:28.876 --> 45:30.918
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS, CHEERS)

45:31.876 --> 45:32.792
<i>And last Friday,</i>

45:32.876 --> 45:34.250
<i>Aviation's version
of the Oscars--</i>

45:34.334 --> 45:37.250
I want you to know
how proud I am to be a pilot.

45:37.334 --> 45:39.751
It's got a lot
of the same qualities

45:39.834 --> 45:41.250
that go into being a musician.

45:41.334 --> 45:43.459
You have to practice,
you have to work hard--

45:43.542 --> 45:45.083
You also are an investor.

45:45.167 --> 45:48.125
How did you select
Starbucks as an investment?

45:48.209 --> 45:51.792
<i>I was one of the original ten
guys that-- part of Starbucks</i>

45:51.876 --> 45:54.667
so that turned out to be
a really great investment.

45:54.751 --> 45:56.542
PENNY: (LAUGHING)
That's like
the understatement...

45:56.626 --> 45:57.667
Yeah.

45:57.751 --> 45:59.834
REPORTER: Give us your best
pirate impression.

45:59.918 --> 46:01.792
I leave that to my son Max.

46:01.876 --> 46:03.000
Arr, matey!

46:03.083 --> 46:04.125
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES CONTINUE) ♪

46:04.209 --> 46:05.500
KENNY G:<i> I have two boys,</i>

46:05.584 --> 46:07.918
<i>so how am I going to become
the best father</i>

46:08.000 --> 46:09.292
<i>the world has ever seen?</i>

46:09.375 --> 46:10.709
<i>I'm gonna start studying it.</i>

46:10.792 --> 46:13.667
<i>So I started reading books.
I started asking questions.</i>

46:13.751 --> 46:16.500
<i>They actually turned out
really, really good.</i>

46:16.584 --> 46:18.209
<i>And, by the way,
both of them grew up</i>

46:18.292 --> 46:19.751
<i>watching their father,</i>

46:19.834 --> 46:21.167
who's already super famous,

46:21.250 --> 46:24.709
every day, practicing,
practicing.

46:28.918 --> 46:31.125
I still haven't hit one
I like yet.

46:31.209 --> 46:33.292
When I do, I'll tell you, okay?

46:33.375 --> 46:37.375
♪ ("SILHOUETTE" PLAYING) ♪

46:43.792 --> 46:46.167
Okay, so I'm not gonna play
Name That Tune with you.

46:46.250 --> 46:47.959
That's "Silhouette" though,
right?

46:48.042 --> 46:53.584
So this is the thing about
"Silhouette" after "Songbird."

46:53.667 --> 46:55.792
Because almost every
instrumental hit

46:55.876 --> 46:57.209
up until this time...

46:59.417 --> 47:01.542
<i>Ramsey Lewis, "The 'In' Crowd."</i>

47:03.876 --> 47:05.876
<i>"Feels So Good,"
Chuck Mangione.</i>

47:07.584 --> 47:10.459
<i>Average White Band,
"Pick Up the Pieces."</i>

47:10.542 --> 47:13.167
You know, tunes that made it
on the pop charts

47:13.250 --> 47:15.000
that were instrumental

47:15.083 --> 47:18.709
kind of became one-hit wonders
in pop radio.

47:18.792 --> 47:21.918
And then here comes Kenny
with a second hit,

47:22.000 --> 47:24.250
and then a third and, you know,
and a fourth.

47:24.334 --> 47:26.959
You could tell that this was
something different.

47:27.042 --> 47:28.417
Hi, this is Kenny G,

47:28.500 --> 47:30.584
and here's my new video
called "Silhouette,"

47:30.667 --> 47:32.375
<i>and I hope you like it.</i>

47:32.459 --> 47:36.250
♪ ("SILHOUETTE" PLAYING) ♪

47:41.125 --> 47:43.709
BEN:<i> He does have a style.</i>
<i>He does have a style.</i>

47:43.792 --> 47:48.250
This intensely gauzy,
very, very breathy thing.

47:48.334 --> 47:53.042
Um, sort of trembly,
uh, lots of dynamics.

47:53.125 --> 47:56.083
And he adds this little extra,

47:56.167 --> 48:01.083
over-the-top, um,
vulnerable emotionality.

48:01.167 --> 48:03.459
Perhaps that
is the Kenny G stamp.

48:05.250 --> 48:08.918
CLIVE: He was coming up
with these melodies

48:09.000 --> 48:12.083
that were unique,
and a style of play

48:12.167 --> 48:14.083
<i>that was unique.</i>

48:14.167 --> 48:19.083
I do have a sixth sense,
in a sense, of melody.

48:19.167 --> 48:20.250
I just do.

48:20.334 --> 48:23.626
I know when the melody is right,
and I know how to--

48:23.709 --> 48:25.792
I know how to come up
with a melody.

48:25.876 --> 48:27.375
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

48:27.918 --> 48:28.918
<i>A lot of times,</i>

48:29.000 --> 48:32.417
<i>I hear the beginning of a song
in my head.</i>

48:32.500 --> 48:34.626
In my practice session,
I'll play a little...

48:34.709 --> 48:35.918
"Ooh, I like that."

48:36.000 --> 48:38.250
"I can hear some chords going on
with that little thing."

48:38.334 --> 48:39.918
"That's gonna turn into a song."

48:40.042 --> 48:42.209
Then I have to find someone
to help me.

48:42.292 --> 48:45.500
I need somebody that knows
the chords,

48:45.584 --> 48:47.584
and will be patient with me
when I go,

48:47.667 --> 48:53.000
"No, no, no, yes, hmm, no, yeah,
hmm, try again,

48:53.083 --> 48:55.500
give me 17 other options
on that chord."

48:55.584 --> 48:57.667
"There's only 12."
"Okay, well, give me all 12."

48:57.751 --> 49:00.000
"There's another one?
Well, yeah, that one."

49:00.083 --> 49:02.626
<i>Music theory will tell you
things about chords</i>

49:02.709 --> 49:04.959
<i>and the notes that go along
with the chords.</i>

49:05.042 --> 49:07.834
<i>But in college, I did not want
to study music theory.</i>

49:07.918 --> 49:09.167
<i>Just didn't appeal to me.</i>

49:09.250 --> 49:10.709
I thought,
"You know what I'm gonna do?"

49:10.792 --> 49:11.959
"I'm gonna take that hour

49:12.042 --> 49:13.626
and go into the practice room
and practice."

49:13.709 --> 49:15.167
So that's what I did.

49:15.250 --> 49:18.375
♪ (SAXOPHONE NOTES PLAYING) ♪

49:20.584 --> 49:23.000
-(DOG YAWNS)
-(LAUGHS)

49:23.083 --> 49:24.876
I know what sounds good to me.

49:24.959 --> 49:26.292
I don't need to know
theoretically

49:26.375 --> 49:28.250
that that note
goes with that note.

49:28.334 --> 49:31.626
<i>And I come up with melodies
that the whole world likes.</i>

49:32.250 --> 49:33.209
<i>I do.</i>

49:33.292 --> 49:35.626
<i>So if I think it sounds good,</i>

49:35.709 --> 49:37.834
it's probably sounding good.

49:37.918 --> 49:41.626
♪ (MELODIC SAXOPHONE
MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

49:43.334 --> 49:47.250
Duotones<i> sold</i>
<i>about 5 million records.</i>

49:50.584 --> 49:52.375
<i>Next record,</i> Silhouette.

49:52.459 --> 49:54.083
<i>Boom, another big hit.</i>

50:01.042 --> 50:04.834
Kenny G Live<i> sold another</i>
<i>four, five million records.</i>

50:08.500 --> 50:11.042
1992,<i> Breathless</i> comes out,

50:11.125 --> 50:13.083
<i>and everything goes bonkers.</i>

50:13.167 --> 50:16.125
<i>And it sells 12 million records.</i>

50:17.667 --> 50:20.334
TV HOST: How would you describe
the kind of music you play?

50:20.417 --> 50:22.709
Well, it's hard to say
in words, you know.

50:22.792 --> 50:26.125
Categorizing it, making some
sort of a descriptive label

50:26.209 --> 50:28.375
will make some people
think one thing

50:28.459 --> 50:29.584
and other people think another.

50:29.667 --> 50:31.876
So you heard it
just a minute ago,

50:31.959 --> 50:33.834
so what do you think?
What's your words for it?

50:33.918 --> 50:35.209
It might be different
than somebody else.

50:35.292 --> 50:36.459
-I think it's sexy.
-Okay.

50:36.542 --> 50:38.834
-Do people call your music sexy?
-Some do.

50:38.918 --> 50:42.083
♪ (MELODIC SAXOPHONE
MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

50:48.042 --> 50:50.584
♪ (SONG CONTINUES OVER RADIO) ♪

50:53.000 --> 50:56.375
BEN:<i> Wasn't part</i>
<i>of the marketing</i>
<i>around Kenny G's music</i>

50:56.459 --> 50:58.500
<i>that it was romantic?</i>

50:58.584 --> 51:01.584
And that maybe
it was like music,

51:01.667 --> 51:04.792
you know, that people wanted
in the background

51:04.876 --> 51:06.959
as they had sex,
and stuff like that?

51:07.042 --> 51:09.751
Yeah. Um...

51:09.834 --> 51:12.417
That's always been a little bit
of a mystery to me.

51:12.834 --> 51:13.918
You know...

51:18.167 --> 51:20.667
♪ (SONG CONTINUES) ♪

51:23.709 --> 51:26.417
Oh, maybe not.
Maybe it makes sense.

51:26.500 --> 51:28.667
Maybe it makes sense.

51:28.751 --> 51:30.209
KENNY G:
<i>People have told me that,</i>
<i>you know.</i>

51:30.292 --> 51:34.083
<i>They'll come and they'll whisper
in my ear what circumstances,</i>

51:34.167 --> 51:36.459
<i>they might have used my music
in very, very intimate,</i>

51:36.542 --> 51:37.667
<i>romantic situations.</i>

51:37.751 --> 51:40.000
It's great. I mean, to be--
To be with somebody

51:40.083 --> 51:42.167
even in a spiritual,
musical sense

51:42.250 --> 51:43.792
when they're either meditating,

51:43.876 --> 51:46.375
making love and relaxing
in a certain way,

51:46.459 --> 51:50.375
getting introspective with
that music of mine helping them.

51:50.459 --> 51:53.209
It's flattering. It's, uh...

51:53.292 --> 51:55.626
I'm glad to be part of it.

51:55.709 --> 51:57.459
I think my music is romantic.

51:57.542 --> 51:59.209
By the way,
I think I'm romantic.

51:59.292 --> 52:01.500
I'm not sure that you would
get that same response

52:01.584 --> 52:03.959
from the people
that are in my life,

52:04.042 --> 52:05.334
the close people in my life.

52:05.417 --> 52:07.584
And I think to myself,
how can I not be romantic

52:07.667 --> 52:10.042
if I can play
this beautiful music

52:10.125 --> 52:11.375
and write these beautiful songs?

52:11.459 --> 52:13.876
I must be at least
somewhat romantic.

52:13.959 --> 52:16.250
People have gotten married
to his music,

52:16.334 --> 52:18.667
had babies by his music.

52:18.751 --> 52:20.542
I mean, in the hospital
and everything.

52:20.626 --> 52:23.626
I have a very good friend
who has twin sons who...

52:23.709 --> 52:28.250
Uh, they played Kenny's music
in the delivery room.

52:28.334 --> 52:29.876
-(PENNY LAUGHING)
-And I will tell you,

52:29.959 --> 52:31.751
the wife was crazy about it.

52:31.834 --> 52:33.000
The husband was like,

52:33.083 --> 52:36.083
"Oh, God, Kenny G
in the delivery..."

52:36.167 --> 52:38.334
(LAUGHS)

52:38.417 --> 52:41.042
His music has been a part
of a lot of our lives

52:41.125 --> 52:44.209
as a soundtrack,
and so as a result of that,

52:44.959 --> 52:46.375
we feel connected to him.

52:47.334 --> 52:53.083
♪ ("GOING HOME" PLAYING) ♪

52:53.167 --> 52:55.292
KENNY G:<i> One of my songs</i>
<i>is super popular in China</i>

52:55.375 --> 52:57.209
<i>called "Going Home."</i>

52:57.292 --> 53:02.792
♪ (VOCALIZES "GOING HOME") ♪

53:02.876 --> 53:04.959
Okay, that's my song.

53:05.042 --> 53:08.584
<i>It's been played now
for over 30 years</i>

53:08.667 --> 53:13.584
<i>every day throughout China
at the end of the day.</i>

53:14.709 --> 53:17.876
<i>They really literally
took the title "Going Home,"</i>

53:17.959 --> 53:20.375
<i>and they decided that this song
is going to be</i>

53:20.459 --> 53:23.209
<i>the national song
for the end of the workday.</i>

53:25.083 --> 53:26.834
<i>They listen, and then they
start packing up,</i>

53:26.918 --> 53:28.292
<i>and it's time to go home.</i>

53:30.209 --> 53:31.876
Yeah, I know. I don't know.

53:32.000 --> 53:33.417
You don't know
how that happened?

53:33.500 --> 53:35.334
I don't know exactly
how that happened.

53:36.876 --> 53:38.375
YIN ZHI YUAN:
(IN MANDARIN)

53:42.417 --> 53:44.709
(IN MANDARIN)

54:01.417 --> 54:02.500
(CHUCKLES)

54:10.334 --> 54:13.292
(IN MANDARIN)

54:22.542 --> 54:24.876
♪ ("GOING HOME" PLAYING) ♪

54:25.918 --> 54:29.125
YIN ZHI YUAN:
(IN MANDARIN)

54:38.083 --> 54:41.918
BEN:<i> The song "Going Home,"</i>
<i>like a lot of his songs,</i>

54:42.000 --> 54:45.500
<i>has a calming effect, I guess,</i>

54:45.584 --> 54:48.167
<i>which will reduce
people's desire</i>

54:48.250 --> 54:51.542
<i>to resist things
or cause trouble.</i>

54:52.375 --> 54:54.334
It's not protesting anything.

54:54.417 --> 54:56.584
It's not against anything.

54:56.667 --> 55:00.167
Is Kenny G's music
a weapon of consent?

55:00.250 --> 55:03.876
You know, like, um,
does it make people...

55:03.959 --> 55:07.584
agree to comply?

55:09.167 --> 55:13.167
Um... And if so, why?

55:13.250 --> 55:15.209
-♪ ("GOING HOME" PLAYING) ♪
-(CHILD YELLING)

55:15.292 --> 55:20.083
YIN ZHI YUAN:
(IN MANDARIN)

55:30.417 --> 55:31.792
(IN MANDARIN)

55:50.834 --> 55:53.918
♪ (PLAYING "GOING HOME") ♪

55:54.000 --> 55:55.459
YIN ZHI YUAN:
(IN MANDARIN)

56:18.292 --> 56:20.000
KENNY G:
<i>I just have to time it perfectly</i>

56:20.083 --> 56:21.459
<i>when I do my shows there,</i>

56:21.542 --> 56:22.959
because the first time
I played it,

56:23.042 --> 56:24.334
I played it in the middle
of the set.

56:24.417 --> 56:25.918
I looked up,
the audience left.

56:27.083 --> 56:29.083
(SPEAKING IN MANDARIN)

56:29.167 --> 56:31.000
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

56:31.083 --> 56:34.792
-(SPEAKING IN MANDARIN)
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

56:34.876 --> 56:36.542
KENNY G:
<i>When I came into the scene,</i>

56:36.626 --> 56:39.292
I created maybe a new sound.

56:39.375 --> 56:40.751
You know, you can call it
what you want,

56:40.834 --> 56:42.834
but you could call it
a new sound of jazz,

56:42.918 --> 56:46.375
a new jazz sound that appealed
to a lot of people.

56:46.459 --> 56:48.626
And I don't think
a lot of people can say

56:48.709 --> 56:51.584
that they created a sound
of music.

56:51.667 --> 56:53.083
And I think I did.

56:53.167 --> 56:55.250
♪ (SMOOTH JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

56:56.250 --> 56:57.751
<i>And then people decided</i>

56:57.834 --> 57:01.500
<i>there should be a whole radio
format like my music.</i>

57:01.584 --> 57:02.709
RADIO HOST:
<i>Welcome to the birth</i>

57:02.792 --> 57:04.834
<i>of Philadelphia's newest
radio station,</i>

57:04.918 --> 57:07.918
<i>WJJZ 106.1 FM.</i>

57:08.000 --> 57:09.959
<i>We're proud to present
a music format</i>

57:10.042 --> 57:12.167
<i>that's never been showcased
here before.</i>

57:12.250 --> 57:13.918
<i>We call it smooth jazz.</i>

57:14.000 --> 57:15.417
<i>In our debut hour,</i>

57:15.500 --> 57:18.000
<i>we'll hear "Champagne"
from Kenny G.</i>

57:18.083 --> 57:21.584
So I became, like,
this face of this sound.

57:21.667 --> 57:24.250
And they decided to call it
"smooth jazz,"

57:24.334 --> 57:27.292
<i>because if they called it jazz,
it was gonna turn people away.</i>

57:28.709 --> 57:29.792
In the late '80s,

57:29.876 --> 57:32.125
the ratings game
was very competitive,

57:32.209 --> 57:35.250
so everybody
was doing research.

57:35.334 --> 57:36.792
<i>We were market researchers,</i>

57:36.876 --> 57:39.292
<i>and we really let the listeners</i>

57:39.375 --> 57:41.626
<i>take over the format.</i>

57:41.709 --> 57:44.500
We would come in and get
at least a hundred people,

57:44.584 --> 57:47.292
and we would run
hooks of songs by them.

57:47.375 --> 57:49.626
<i>They had a little dial
in their hand,</i>

57:49.709 --> 57:50.959
and if they liked it--

57:51.042 --> 57:52.375
What do you do
when you like a song?

57:52.459 --> 57:54.167
<i>You turn it up, like the volume.</i>

57:54.250 --> 57:55.626
<i>So they would just turn it up.</i>

57:55.709 --> 57:57.959
And they could go to 100
if they loved the song.

57:58.042 --> 58:00.209
We would watch these lines
go up and down.

58:01.500 --> 58:02.876
<i>And then Kenny G
would come on...</i>

58:02.959 --> 58:05.918
<i>Right up to the top.
Everybody loved it.</i>

58:06.000 --> 58:08.417
Nine out of the top 15 songs
would be Kenny G songs,

58:08.500 --> 58:11.626
out of, like, 650 songs
that we researched.

58:11.709 --> 58:13.167
<i>And then we would say,</i>

58:13.250 --> 58:15.959
<i>"Just tell us what words
pop to mind."</i>

58:16.042 --> 58:17.500
<i>And almost everybody would say,</i>

58:17.584 --> 58:19.834
"It's jazz, but..."

58:19.918 --> 58:23.459
And I still-- I still remember
this woman's face.

58:23.542 --> 58:25.459
I can see it as clear as day.

58:25.542 --> 58:29.250
She's thinking, she says,
"It's jazz."

58:29.334 --> 58:31.459
She said,
"It's smooth jazz."

58:31.542 --> 58:34.792
It was almost like it just came
to her like a lightning bolt.

58:34.876 --> 58:36.417
And we were all like,
"That's it."

58:36.500 --> 58:38.042
You know, I mean,
that's got to be it.

58:39.626 --> 58:42.584
<i>WNUA in Chicago was the first
station in the country</i>

58:42.667 --> 58:44.167
<i>to use the term "smooth jazz."</i>

58:44.250 --> 58:46.584
<i>You know, it later
was adopted in a lot of places</i>

58:46.667 --> 58:49.042
<i>where we were consulting.</i>

58:49.125 --> 58:51.083
MAN:<i> You're a bit too old</i>
<i>for rock and roll</i>

58:51.167 --> 58:54.542
and classical music for you
might be a little cerebral.

58:54.626 --> 58:56.626
And jazz is a little esoteric.

58:56.709 --> 58:58.709
But you want to be part
of what's going on in music.

58:58.792 --> 59:00.209
<i>What's for me?</i>

59:01.125 --> 59:02.751
I listen to it at work.

59:02.834 --> 59:04.542
Uh, actually, I listen to it
all the time.

59:04.626 --> 59:07.209
It fits in perfectly
with everything I do.

59:07.292 --> 59:10.500
I think I perform better.
I hope my bosses say that.

59:10.584 --> 59:11.792
I've never heard music
like this...

59:11.876 --> 59:15.542
This format got a lot
of traction in offices.

59:15.626 --> 59:18.959
<i>It was something that everybody
could agree on</i>

59:19.042 --> 59:20.250
<i>in the office.</i>

59:20.334 --> 59:22.125
<i>No one was going to be offended</i>

59:22.209 --> 59:24.125
<i>by anything that you hear.</i>

59:24.209 --> 59:27.209
<i>It was never too loud or rowdy.</i>

59:27.292 --> 59:29.334
<i>But it also had enough tempo</i>

59:29.417 --> 59:30.876
<i>to keep it interesting,</i>

59:30.959 --> 59:33.250
to have you nod your head
a little bit.

59:33.334 --> 59:36.792
ALLEN KEPLER:
<i>The key was to make it</i>
<i>palatable for a big tent.</i>

59:36.876 --> 59:39.751
<i>There are certain people
that love smooth jazz</i>

59:39.834 --> 59:43.083
that would never listen to jazz.

59:43.167 --> 59:45.083
And we used to hear this
in focus groups.

59:45.167 --> 59:49.500
"I didn't really know
I liked jazz, but I like this."

59:50.417 --> 59:53.584
♪ ("SENTIMENTAL" PLAYING) ♪

59:59.334 --> 1:00:02.083
CHRIS:
<i>In the 1980s and the 1990s,</i>

1:00:02.167 --> 1:00:05.292
<i>traditional jazz had been quite
marginalized economically,</i>

1:00:05.375 --> 1:00:08.459
and the opportunities for jazz
musicians were dwindling.

1:00:08.542 --> 1:00:12.209
But at the same time,
you have someone named Kenny G,

1:00:12.292 --> 1:00:15.292
and some other musicians, too,
that were playing in this

1:00:15.375 --> 1:00:18.334
that were being extremely
successful financially,

1:00:18.417 --> 1:00:21.667
and they were using
that four letter word "jazz."

1:00:21.751 --> 1:00:24.667
<i>He was having a huge impact
on society,</i>

1:00:24.751 --> 1:00:27.918
<i>in terms of defining
what jazz is,</i>

1:00:28.000 --> 1:00:30.375
<i>even though within
the jazz community,</i>

1:00:30.459 --> 1:00:32.709
<i>people were looking
at his music with disdain</i>

1:00:32.792 --> 1:00:34.542
<i>and really distancing themselves</i>

1:00:34.626 --> 1:00:36.167
<i>from what he was doing.</i>

1:00:40.626 --> 1:00:42.375
WILL LAYMAN:<i> People sometimes</i>
<i>legitimately ask,</i>

1:00:42.459 --> 1:00:44.000
<i>you know,
"Why do jazz musicians..."</i>

1:00:44.083 --> 1:00:46.375
"Why are they so irritated
by Kenny G?"

1:00:46.459 --> 1:00:49.042
And I was thinking about this
and, you know,

1:00:49.125 --> 1:00:53.000
<i>the Harlem Globetrotters
are a basketball team</i>

1:00:53.083 --> 1:00:55.500
<i>that's existed for decades.</i>

1:00:55.584 --> 1:00:58.167
♪ (LIGHTHEARTED MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

1:00:59.959 --> 1:01:02.500
WILL:<i> And they do not play</i>
<i>competitive basketball.</i>

1:01:02.584 --> 1:01:04.834
<i>They are a group
of entertainers,</i>

1:01:04.918 --> 1:01:07.334
<i>and they spin the basketball
on their finger,</i>

1:01:07.417 --> 1:01:10.250
<i>and they do trick shots,
and they clown around.</i>

1:01:10.334 --> 1:01:12.542
<i>I would say that most players
in the NBA</i>

1:01:12.626 --> 1:01:14.000
<i>love the Globetrotters.</i>

1:01:14.083 --> 1:01:16.042
But imagine a world

1:01:16.125 --> 1:01:20.167
in which legitimate
competitive basketball

1:01:20.250 --> 1:01:21.542
is not popular,

1:01:21.626 --> 1:01:25.709
and LeBron James
and Michael Jordan in his day,

1:01:25.792 --> 1:01:29.209
they worked their whole lives
to be great basketball players,

1:01:29.292 --> 1:01:31.250
and now the only way
they can afford the rent

1:01:31.334 --> 1:01:35.500
on their apartment is
to part-time be, like, waiters.

1:01:35.584 --> 1:01:38.542
<i>Imagine how they would feel
about the Harlem Globetrotters</i>

1:01:38.626 --> 1:01:40.334
<i>spinning the ball
on their finger</i>

1:01:40.417 --> 1:01:42.417
<i>and making a lot of money
from it.</i>

1:01:42.500 --> 1:01:44.542
<i>And I think that's
how jazz musicians</i>

1:01:44.626 --> 1:01:46.584
feel about Kenny G.

1:01:46.667 --> 1:01:49.751
-♪ (PLAYING SINGLE NOTE) ♪
-(AUDIENCE CHUCKLES)

1:01:53.792 --> 1:01:57.792
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS, APPLAUDS)
-♪ (NOTE CONTINUES) ♪

1:01:59.375 --> 1:02:02.626
Every single
jazz saxophone player

1:02:02.709 --> 1:02:04.042
can do circular breathing,

1:02:04.125 --> 1:02:07.292
and every player in the NBA can
spin the ball on their finger

1:02:07.375 --> 1:02:09.459
and, like, have it roll
across their shoulders.

1:02:09.542 --> 1:02:12.459
They can all do it because
it's fun and they do it.

1:02:12.542 --> 1:02:13.834
But it's not basketball.

1:02:13.918 --> 1:02:16.459
♪ (UPBEAT SAXOPHONE
NOTES PLAYING) ♪

1:02:19.876 --> 1:02:22.918
JASON:<i> You know, to me,</i>
<i>I look at him in two ways.</i>

1:02:23.000 --> 1:02:24.959
<i>On one hand,
he's introduced people</i>

1:02:25.042 --> 1:02:26.751
<i>all over the world to jazz</i>

1:02:26.834 --> 1:02:29.876
<i>in a way that is probably
unquantifiable,</i>

1:02:29.959 --> 1:02:31.584
given the number of records
that he's sold.

1:02:31.667 --> 1:02:33.626
There's a lot of people
for whom they would never

1:02:33.709 --> 1:02:36.667
have heard jazz unless
they had first heard Kenny G.

1:02:36.751 --> 1:02:38.667
And maybe it was
a kind of gateway

1:02:38.751 --> 1:02:40.292
into all kinds of other jazz.

1:02:40.375 --> 1:02:41.709
It certainly was for me.

1:02:41.792 --> 1:02:43.250
And yet, at the same time,

1:02:43.334 --> 1:02:46.667
he seems to draw from
this rich and venerated history

1:02:46.751 --> 1:02:50.292
of Black music without
necessarily contributing much

1:02:50.375 --> 1:02:51.626
back to the form.

1:02:51.709 --> 1:02:52.751
PRESENTER: ...artist, Kenny G!

1:02:52.834 --> 1:02:54.250
<i>He's such a deeply
problematic figure,</i>

1:02:54.334 --> 1:02:59.000
<i>because he really extends
this long and troubling history</i>

1:02:59.083 --> 1:03:01.250
<i>of appropriation
in popular music</i>

1:03:01.334 --> 1:03:03.459
where Black artists innovate,

1:03:03.542 --> 1:03:05.292
and then white artists
come along and stylize,

1:03:05.375 --> 1:03:07.918
and then receive greater
financial renumeration,

1:03:08.000 --> 1:03:09.959
and greater critical acclaim.

1:03:10.042 --> 1:03:12.042
Never th-- I've honestly never
put a lot of thought

1:03:12.125 --> 1:03:16.083
into the color of my skin,
and my career, and my success.

1:03:16.626 --> 1:03:17.876
Honestly haven't.

1:03:17.959 --> 1:03:20.542
<i>I mean, if I was a Black guy,</i>

1:03:20.626 --> 1:03:22.709
<i>would Clive Davis
have signed me as easily?</i>

1:03:22.792 --> 1:03:24.042
I think he probably would have.

1:03:24.125 --> 1:03:26.167
I don't think that
would have made a difference.

1:03:26.250 --> 1:03:29.209
Would I have been as big
of an artist, you know?

1:03:29.292 --> 1:03:32.292
Then we have to look at what was
pop radio like in,

1:03:32.375 --> 1:03:33.709
let's say, 1986.

1:03:33.792 --> 1:03:35.500
Because that's when I had
my song "Songbird."

1:03:35.584 --> 1:03:38.000
Are they more apt to play it
because I'm white?

1:03:38.083 --> 1:03:41.000
What if I was a Black guy
with the same song?

1:03:41.083 --> 1:03:42.209
They might go,

1:03:42.292 --> 1:03:45.167
"You know, we'll leave that
to the R&B stations."

1:03:45.250 --> 1:03:49.375
So I'm gonna say I probably
benefited from that.

1:03:50.083 --> 1:03:51.292
I'm kind of thinking

1:03:51.375 --> 1:03:53.000
that I got that door
opened for me.

1:03:53.083 --> 1:03:54.500
Yeah. I think
that's a good question.

1:03:54.584 --> 1:03:56.292
I've never really
thought about it like that,

1:03:56.375 --> 1:03:59.083
and I think-- I think
I benefited.

1:03:59.167 --> 1:04:01.709
I mean, historically,
in this country,

1:04:01.792 --> 1:04:04.709
certainly, African American
artists who have--

1:04:04.792 --> 1:04:07.918
You know, who are great players
with incredible talent,

1:04:08.000 --> 1:04:10.292
who get to watch others,
you know,

1:04:10.375 --> 1:04:13.083
like your Elvis Presley's
and all these people,

1:04:13.167 --> 1:04:16.876
take their music
and then become rich from it.

1:04:16.959 --> 1:04:19.042
That's not a fun thing to watch.

1:04:19.125 --> 1:04:23.209
I can understand where some
of the resentment comes from.

1:04:23.292 --> 1:04:26.918
♪ (SAXOPHONE PLAYS TUNE OF
