<i>♪ What a wonderful world ♪</i>

1:05:02.334 --> 1:05:04.417
KENNY G:<i> The Louis Armstrong</i>
<i>duet happened</i>

1:05:04.500 --> 1:05:07.292
<i>when I was sitting
in my driveway in Seattle.</i>

1:05:07.375 --> 1:05:09.751
I just got through hearing
that song...

1:05:09.834 --> 1:05:11.459
<i>♪ Unforgettable ♪</i>

1:05:11.542 --> 1:05:13.876
♪ (UNFORGETTABLE
BY NAT KING COLE PLAYS) ♪

1:05:13.959 --> 1:05:15.209
KENNY G:<i> With Natalie Cole</i>

1:05:15.292 --> 1:05:17.667
<i>and her late father,
Nat King Cole.</i>

1:05:19.167 --> 1:05:22.292
I thought,
"Wow, that's cool."

1:05:22.375 --> 1:05:24.417
"I want do a song like that."

1:05:25.876 --> 1:05:27.584
<i>We needed permission to do it,</i>

1:05:27.667 --> 1:05:29.500
<i>from the Louis Armstrong
Foundation.</i>

1:05:29.584 --> 1:05:31.459
And we said, "Look, we want
to give all the money

1:05:31.542 --> 1:05:32.834
to whatever charity you want.

1:05:32.918 --> 1:05:35.959
<i>And we want to pay tribute
to this beautiful song."</i>

1:05:36.042 --> 1:05:37.542
And it became a huge hit.

1:05:37.626 --> 1:05:39.167
But there's a few musicians
out there

1:05:39.250 --> 1:05:41.167
that felt protective of

1:05:41.250 --> 1:05:42.959
Louis Armstrong and his legacy,

1:05:43.042 --> 1:05:45.417
and they felt like it was
tainted by me playing with him,

1:05:45.500 --> 1:05:47.626
and they were very vocal
about it.

1:05:47.709 --> 1:05:49.876
♪ (GUITAR TUNE PLAYING) ♪

1:05:51.292 --> 1:05:54.334
KENNY G:<i> It was a guitar player</i>
<i>named Pat Metheny.</i>

1:05:54.417 --> 1:05:56.751
BEN:<i> Pat Metheny</i>
<i>had written something</i>

1:05:56.834 --> 1:05:59.542
<i>like a screed against the song</i>

1:05:59.626 --> 1:06:02.667
<i>and against what Kenny G
was doing.</i>

1:06:02.751 --> 1:06:05.292
CHRIS:<i> He is highly respected</i>
<i>in the jazz world,</i>

1:06:05.375 --> 1:06:07.709
<i>so that was kind of like
jazz aristocracy</i>

1:06:07.792 --> 1:06:10.334
<i>coming out and speaking
against Kenny G.</i>

1:06:10.417 --> 1:06:12.292
-COMPUTER:<i> You've got mail.</i>
-BEN:<i> More and more people</i>

1:06:12.375 --> 1:06:15.125
<i>started forwarding me
this thing.</i>

1:06:15.209 --> 1:06:16.542
(EMAIL NOTIFICATION TUNE)

1:06:16.626 --> 1:06:19.459
It was a moment
of going viral,

1:06:19.542 --> 1:06:20.792
but through email.

1:06:20.876 --> 1:06:22.500
(NOTIFICATIONS CONTINUE)

1:06:23.626 --> 1:06:25.334
You want me to read it
out loud for you?

1:06:27.542 --> 1:06:29.834
"This type of musical
necrophilia

1:06:29.918 --> 1:06:33.209
<i>was weird when Natalie Cole
did it with her dad,</i>

1:06:33.292 --> 1:06:35.000
but it was her dad."

1:06:35.083 --> 1:06:37.500
"When Kenny G decided
that it was appropriate

1:06:37.584 --> 1:06:40.042
for him to defile the music
of the man

1:06:40.125 --> 1:06:41.918
<i>who's probably the greatest
jazz musician</i>

1:06:42.000 --> 1:06:45.042
<i>that has ever lived
by spewing his lame-ass..."</i>

1:06:45.125 --> 1:06:48.876
JOHN:<i> "...jive, pseudo-bluesy,</i>
<i>out-of-tune noodling..."</i>

1:06:48.959 --> 1:06:51.292
BEN:<i> "...wimped-out,</i>
<i>fucked-up playing</i>

1:06:51.375 --> 1:06:53.834
all over one
of Louis' tracks..."

1:06:53.918 --> 1:06:55.167
"...he did something

1:06:55.250 --> 1:06:57.292
that I would not have
imagined possible."

1:06:57.375 --> 1:07:00.584
JOHN:
<i>"He shit all over the graves</i>
<i>of all the musicians</i>

1:07:00.667 --> 1:07:04.334
who have risked their lives
by going out there on the road

1:07:04.417 --> 1:07:07.375
for years and years,
developing their own music..."

1:07:07.459 --> 1:07:10.709
"...inspired by the standards
of grace that Louis Armstrong

1:07:10.792 --> 1:07:13.000
<i>brought to every single note
that he played."</i>

1:07:13.083 --> 1:07:16.250
"There are some things
that are sacred."

1:07:17.417 --> 1:07:18.751
<i>"And amongst any musician</i>

1:07:18.834 --> 1:07:20.834
that has ever attempted
to address jazz

1:07:20.918 --> 1:07:22.918
at even the most basic
of levels,

1:07:23.000 --> 1:07:26.459
Louis Armstrong and his music
is hallowed ground."

1:07:26.542 --> 1:07:29.751
"By disrespecting Louis,
his legacy and, by default..."

1:07:29.834 --> 1:07:32.876
"Everyone who has ever
tried to do something positive

1:07:32.959 --> 1:07:34.334
with improvised music..."

1:07:34.417 --> 1:07:39.125
"Kenny G has created a new
low point in modern culture,

1:07:39.209 --> 1:07:42.959
something that we should all
be totally embarrassed about

1:07:43.042 --> 1:07:45.209
and afraid of."

1:07:45.292 --> 1:07:48.459
"We ignore this
at our own peril."

1:07:48.542 --> 1:07:51.042
That's the line
that always gets me.

1:07:51.125 --> 1:07:53.459
"The only reason
he could possibly have

1:07:53.542 --> 1:07:55.751
for doing something
this inherently wrong

1:07:55.834 --> 1:07:58.042
on both human
and musical terms

1:07:58.125 --> 1:08:01.125
was for the record sales
and the money it would bring."

1:08:01.209 --> 1:08:03.584
"Everything I said here
is exactly the same

1:08:03.667 --> 1:08:07.250
as what I would say to Gorelick
if I ever saw him in person."

1:08:07.334 --> 1:08:09.292
"And if I ever do see him,

1:08:09.375 --> 1:08:10.959
he will get a piece of my mind,

1:08:11.042 --> 1:08:14.292
and maybe a guitar
wrapped around his head."

1:08:16.751 --> 1:08:18.500
He's entitled to his opinion.

1:08:20.000 --> 1:08:21.834
<i>I think he was being
super protective</i>

1:08:21.918 --> 1:08:24.542
<i>of the traditional jazz genre,</i>

1:08:24.626 --> 1:08:26.751
and I understand it.

1:08:26.834 --> 1:08:28.209
So I'm not mad at him.

1:08:28.292 --> 1:08:31.751
I never get mad at anybody
for pretty much anything...

1:08:33.292 --> 1:08:35.959
because it doesn't do me
any good.

1:08:36.042 --> 1:08:37.876
I mean, when have you ever
gotten mad at somebody

1:08:37.959 --> 1:08:39.292
and then they go,

1:08:39.375 --> 1:08:41.334
"You're right, I was wrong"?

1:08:41.417 --> 1:08:42.459
Nobody ever does that.

1:08:42.542 --> 1:08:43.959
<i>Sometimes you say
the word "jazz,"</i>

1:08:44.042 --> 1:08:46.292
<i>and people think of some
of the worst music on earth.</i>

1:08:46.375 --> 1:08:48.584
<i>Like, for instance, Kenny G.
I mean, you know,</i>

1:08:48.667 --> 1:08:51.292
<i>there's nothing more stupid
than that, let's face it.</i>

1:08:51.375 --> 1:08:54.542
<i>That's the dumbest music
there ever could possibly be</i>

1:08:54.626 --> 1:08:56.500
<i>in the history
of human beings.</i>

1:08:56.584 --> 1:09:02.042
Pat Metheny was attacking
the song within a jazz context.

1:09:02.125 --> 1:09:03.918
<i>From my point of view,
I felt that</i>

1:09:04.000 --> 1:09:06.876
<i>both Kenny G
and Louis Armstrong,</i>

1:09:06.959 --> 1:09:09.209
via that song,
"What a Wonderful World,"

